ode [coordinate, right=2cm of plant] (output) {}; \draw [line] (input) -- node {Reference} (controller); \draw [line] (controller) -- node {Input} (plant); \draw [line] (plant) -- node [name=y] {Output} (output); \draw [line] (y.south) |- ++(0,-1.5) -| node [pos=0.25, below] {Measurements} (controller.south); \caption{The Classical Control Loop. The controller is a pre-designed dynamic block (e.g., PID) that maps error to input of the controlled system called plant.} To give an example, in classical control (e.g., Proportional-Integral-Derivative or PID), the engineer explicitly defines how the controller calculates the input. The internal structure of a PID controller is shown in Figure~. A PID controller is explicitly instructed to: \item Calculate the error, $e(t)=r(t)-y(t)$ (Reference - Output). \item Integrate the error, $\int e(t)dt$. \item Differentiate the error, $\dfrac{d}{dt}e(t)$. \item Multiply these terms by specific gains ($K_p, K_i, K_d$) and sum them to obtain control signal, $$u(t)=K_pe(t)+K_i \int e(t)dt+K_d rac{d}{dt}e(t)$$ This sum constitutes the control input that is applied to the plant. The behaviour is fixed by the mathematical structure of the controller. That means when one knows $e(t)$ numerically and once the control gains ($K_p, K_i, K_d$) are selected, the control signal applied to the plant can be precisely calculated in closed form. [t] \centering 
