As shown in Figure~, MPC takes a different approach. In an MPC architecture, the explicit controller block is replaced by an optimisation routine. Here we call it Optimiser. This is typically an embedded digital computer that runs an algorithm. Instead of specifying how to calculate the input mathematically, MPC specifies what the controller should achieve. That is, no explicit controller structure is specified; instead, the optimiser directly generates the control signal. Even if the error signal $e(t)$ is known, we cannot predict what the controller will generate. The signal generated by the optimiser that goes into the Plant depends on many factors and conditions of the controller, measured signal, dynamics of the plant, reference signal, environmental conditions, and their current, past and predicted values. Generally, the engineer provides the optimiser with four key components: \item A Model (Plant dynamics): Information on how the plant reacts to inputs and disturbances (typically a state-space model derived from first principles like Newton's second law of motion, Kirchhoff's voltage and current laws for electrical circuits). \item Measurements: The current state $x(t)$ of the system and historical data. This could be either a measured signal or estimated one. \item Objectives: A mathematical function cost representing the goal (e.g., tracking a reference or minimising energy consumption). \item Constraints: Limitations on the system (e.g., maximum valve opening, safety limits, temperature limits, rate bounds of the actuator etc.). [t] \centering [auto, node distance=2.5cm, >={Latex[length=3mm, width=2mm]}, thick] 	ikzset{block/.style={draw, rectangle, fill=gray!30, minimum height=4em, minimum width=6em, text width=6em, align=center}} 	ikzset{line/.style={draw, ->}} 	ikzset{coord/.style={coordinate}} 
