The RHC strategy operates in discrete time steps. At each sampling instant $t$, the controller performs the following sequence, as illustrated in Figure~: \item Measure: Obtain the current state of the system, denoted as $x(t)$ via sensors or estimators. This provides the starting line for the current iteration. \item Plan (Optimise): Using an internal model of the plant, calculate an optimal sequence of future control inputs $\{u_0, u_1, \dots, u_{N-1}\}$ over a finite prediction horizon $N$. This sequence is chosen to minimise a cost function (such as error from a reference) whilst respecting all physical constraints. \item Execute: Although a full sequence of $N$ steps was calculated, the controller applies only the first element, $u_0$, to the plant. The remaining $N-1$ steps of the plan are discarded. \item Evolve: The system evolves for one sample period under the influence of the applied input and any external disturbances. \item Repeat: At the next time step $t+1$, the entire process begins again. The horizon "recedes" (shifts forward by one step), and a new optimisation problem is solved from the new state $x(t+1)$. [h] \centering esizebox{0.85	extwidth}{!}{ [auto, >={Latex[length=3mm, width=2mm]}, thick] 	ikzset{block/.style={draw, rectangle, fill=gray!30, minimum height=4em, minimum width=6em, align=center}} 	ikzset{line/.style={draw, ->}} 
