The final piece of the MPC puzzle is the strategy of implementation. As illustrated in Figure~, and shown in the flow chart Figure~, the process operates in closed loop, but still relying on an open-loop anticipation. At every specific time step $t$, the controller solves the optimisation problem to find the optimal sequence of future control inputs, denoted as ${U}^\star$: {U}^\star = \{u^\star_{0}, u^\star_{1}, \dots, u^\star_{N-1}\} = \arg \min_{{U}} J(x_0, {U}) This sequence represents a complete plan for the next $N$ time steps. For example, in a self-driving car, this sequence might represent the steering angles for the next 10 seconds. However, MPC does not implement the entire plan but instead proceeds as follows: \item Extract: Take only the first element of the optimal sequence, $u^\star_{0}$. \item Apply: Send this single signal to the plant actuators. \item Discard: Throw away the remaining calculated inputs ($u^\star_{1} \dots u^\star_{N-1}$). \item Evolve: Wait for one sample step ($t 	o t+1$), measure the new state $x_{t+1}$, and shift the horizon forward by one step. \item Repeat: Solve the entire optimisation problem again from scratch. 	ikzset{block/.style={rectangle, draw, fill=blue!10, text width=8em, text centered, rounded corners, minimum height=3em}} 	ikzset{cloud/.style={ellipse, draw, fill=red!10, text width=4em, text centered, minimum height=2.5em}} 	ikzset{line/.style={draw, -latex', thick}} [htbp] \centering [node distance=2.5cm, auto] 
