ode[rotate=-17] at (0.4, -0.25) {\small $1-2x$}; \captionof{figure}{Box volume maximisation problem.} \solution We map this problem to the three components of optimisation: \item Decision Variable ($x$): The size of the corner cut. \item Constraints: \item The cut must be positive: $x \geq 0$. \item The cut cannot overlap (total width is 1m): $2x \leq 1 \implies x \leq 0.5$. \item Objective Function: Maximise Volume $V = 	ext{length} 	imes 	ext{width} 	imes 	ext{height}$. \[ J(x) = \underbrace{(1-2x) \cdot (1-2x)}_{Base Area} \cdot x = x(1-2x)^2 \] Mathematical Formulation: ootnote{ Note on Standard Form: While this example seeks to maximise volume, most standard solvers (including quadprog in MATLAB) are designed to minimise functions. In engineering practice, we simply flip the sign of the objective function. Maximising $f(x)$ is mathematically equivalent to minimising $-f(x)$.} \max_{x} \quad & x(1-2x)^2 	ext{s.t.} \quad & 0 \leq x \leq 0.5 or equivalently \min \quad & -x(1-2x)^2 	ext{s.t.} \quad & 0 \leq x \leq 0.5 {Linear Regression (Least Squares)} Problem Statement: Suppose we are given a dataset containing $N$ pairs of experimental measurements: $\{(x_1, y_1), (x_2, y_2), \dots, (x_N, y_N)\}$ as shown in Figure~. We want to find the linear model (a straight line) that "best fits" this data. [scale=0.8] \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (6,0) node[right] {$x$}; \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (0,5) node[above] {$y$}; \draw[step=1cm, gray!20, very thin] (0,0) grid (5.9,4.9); \draw[blue, very thick] (0,1) -- (5.5, 4.3) node[right] {$\hat{y} = a^T x + b$};  oreach \p/\x/\y in {1/1/2.2, 2/2/1.5, 3/3/3.5, 4/4/3.0, 5/5/4.5} { \draw[dashed, red, thick] (\x, \y) -- (\x, {0.6*\x + 1});  ill[red] (\x, \y) circle (3pt); } 
ode[red, above] at (1, 2.2) {	iny $(x_1, y_1)$}; 
ode[right, red] at (3, 3.1) {	iny error}; \captionof{figure}{Dataset (red), linear interpolation (blue).} \solution Note that in this specific problem, the $x$ values are constants (data we measured), not decision variables. \item Decision Variables: The parameters of the line: the slope vector $a \in \mathbb{R}^n$ and the intercept $b \in \mathbb{R}$. \item Note: In the 2D plot above, $n=1$, so $a$ is a scalar slope. However, the math holds for $n$-dimensional vectors. \item Objective Function: We define the prediction for the $i$-th data point as $\hat{y}_i = a^T x_i + b$. We want to minimise the Sum of Squared Errors (SSE): \[ J(a, b) = \sum_{i=1}^{N} (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2 = \sum_{i=1}^{N} \left( y_i - (a^T x_i + b) ight)^2 \] \item Constraints: In this case, $a$ and $b$ can be any real numbers. There are no restrictions. Therefore this is an unconstrained optimisation. Mathematical Formulation: \min_{a, b} \quad \sum_{i=1}^{N} \left( y_i - (a^T x_i + b) ight)^2

function} The mathematical notation $J: \mathbb{R}^n 	o \mathbb{R}$ often confuses beginners. It reads: "The function $f$ takes a vector of $n$ numbers and transforms it into a single real number." To understand why this is necessary, let us consider a relatable real-world analogy: The Shopping Basket. \subsubsection*{The Analogy} Imagine you are at a supermarket checkout. \item The Vector ($x$): Your shopping basket contains many different items. You might have 2 loaves of bread, 6 eggs, and 1 litre of milk. We can list these quantities as a vector: \[ x = 2 6 1 \leftarrow 	ext{Bread} \leftarrow 	ext{Eggs} \leftarrow 	ext{Milk} \] This vector represents the state of your shopping. It is multi-dimensional because it contains different types of information. \item The Objective Function ($J$): The checkout till scans your items. It applies a specific rule (the price list) to your vector. It multiplies each item by its value and sums them up: \[ J(x) = (2 	imes \pounds 1.00) + (6 	imes \pounds 0.20) + (1 	imes \pounds 0.80) \] \item The Scalar ($J$): The till produces a single number: {\pounds 4.00}. This is visually described in Figure~. [node distance=2cm, auto, >=latex', thick] 
