ode [below=0.5cm of func] {\small The Objective Function}; \captionof{figure}{Analogy of cost function.} \subsubsection*{Why is this important in Engineering?} You cannot easily say which of two shopping baskets is larger just by looking at the items—one might have more eggs but no milk. However, once you map them to a {scalar} (the total price), comparison becomes easy. You can instantly say which basket costs less. In Model Predictive Control, our basket ($x$) contains complex decisions: valve positions, heater settings, and motor speeds over the next 20 minutes. We cannot simply look at two different plans and say Plan A is better than Plan B, because Plan A might use less fuel but Plan B might track the temperature better. The objective function $J(x)$ squashes all these complex, multi-dimensional decisions into a single number (a score). \item If Plan A scores $10.5$ and Plan B scores $8.2$, and we are minimising cost, we know for a fact that {Plan B is the mathematical winner}. {Key Takeaway} Optimisation algorithms cannot minimise a list or a vector. They can only minimise a single number. The objective function acts as a translator, converting a complex list of engineering decisions into a single score that allows us to rank them.

We rarely operate in an ideal world. Our decisions are restricted by physical limits. These restrictions are defined by a finite number of equations or inequalities involving the decision variables. \item Inequality Constraints ($g_i$): These represent bounds, such as "Temperature must be less than $100^{\circ}\mathrm{C}$" or "Valve must be open at least 10\%". \[ g_i(x) \leq b_i, \quad i = 1, \dots, m \] \item Equality Constraints ($h_j$): These represent strict physics or model dynamics, such as Input flow must equal output flow or $F = ma$. \[ h_j(x) = 0, \quad j = 1, \dots, q \] \item Domain Restrictions: Sometimes variables are not continuous. For instance, a switch is either ON (1) or OFF (0). If $p$ variables are discrete (integers) and the rest are continuous, we denote the domain as $x \in \mathbb{R}^{n-p} 	imes \mathbb{Z}^p$. Note that dealing with domain restrictions is difficult in optimisation. Collectively, these constraints define a specific region in the $n$-dimensional space called the Feasible Set $S$. The optimisation algorithm is only allowed to search for solutions within this set. S = \{ x \in \mathbb{R}^n \mid g_i(x) \leq b_i \  orall i, \ h_j(x) = 0 \  orall j \} If the intersection of these constraints is empty (e.g., $x > 5$ AND $x < 3$), the problem is infeasible—there is no solution. {Visualising the Feasible Set} Consider a 2-dimensional problem ($x \in \mathbb{R}^2$) with two inequality constraints: \item $g_1(x) = x_1^2 + x_2^2 \leq 4$ (Must be inside a circle of radius 2). \item $g_2(x) = x_1^3 - x_2 \leq 0 \implies x_2 \geq x_1^3$ (Must be above the cubic curve). The feasible set $S$ is the intersection of these two regions (the purple area as shown in Figure~). [scale=1.2] \draw[->] (-2.5,0) -- (2.5,0) node[right] {$x_1$}; \draw[->] (0,-2.5) -- (0,2.5) node[above] {$x_2$};  ill[red!30, opacity=0.7] (0,0) circle (2cm); \clip (-2.5, -2.5) rectangle (2.5, 2.5);  ill[blue!30, opacity=0.6] plot[domain=-2:2, samples=50] (\x, {\x*\x*\x}) |