abla f$, is a column vector containing the partial derivatives with respect to $x_1$ and $x_2$: a = 
abla_x f = \dfrac{\partial f}{\partial x_1} [12pt] \dfrac{\partial f}{\partial x_2} = 2 1 This confirms that the vector $a = (2, 1)^	op$ is the gradient of the linear function defining the hyperplane. Geometrically, the gradient vector is perpendicular to the level sets of the function, meaning $a$ is perpendicular to the line $2x_1 + x_2 = 2$, as shown in Figure . [scale=1.5, >=stealth] \draw[step=0.5cm, gray!20, very thin] (-2.5,-1.5) grid (3.5,3.5); \draw[<->, thick] (-2.5,0) -- (3.5,0) node[right] {$x_1$}; \draw[<->, thick] (0,-1.5) -- (0,3.5) node[above] {$x_2$}; \draw[thick, black] (-0.5, 3) -- (1.5, -1) node[midway, sloped, above, yshift=2pt] {$2x_1 + x_2 = 2$};  illdraw (0,2) circle (1.5pt) node[above right] {$(0,2)$};  illdraw (1,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$(1,0)$}; \coordinate (P) at (0.5, 1); \draw[->, red, thick] (P) -- ++(1, 0.5) node[right] {$a = 2 1 $}; \draw[thick] ($(P)!0.2cm!-63.4:(1.5,-1)$) -- ++(26.6:0.2) -- ($(P)!0.2cm!26.6:(1.5,1.5)$); 
