Let $S$ be a convex subset of a vector space. We define the properties of functions mapping $S$ to the real numbers $\mathbb{R}$ as follows. {Convex Function} A function $f: S ightarrow \mathbb{R}$ is said to be convex if $S$ is convex and the following inequality holds for all $z_1, z_2 \in S$ and for all $\lambda \in [0, 1]$: f(\lambda z_1 + (1 - \lambda)z_2) \leq \lambda f(z_1) + (1 - \lambda)f(z_2) Geometrically, this means that the line segment connecting any two points on the graph of the function lies above or on the graph between the two points. {Concave Function} A function $f: S ightarrow \mathbb{R}$ is concave if $S$ is convex and $-f$ is a convex function. Equivalently, the inequality in the definition of convexity is reversed. The concept of convexity is illustrated in Figure . The curve represents the function $f$. The red secant line connects two points $(z_1, f(z_1))$ and $(z_2, f(z_2))$. For a convex function, the value of the function evaluated at a weighted average of two points (the black dot on the curve) is always less than or equal to the weighted average of the function values (the black dot on the red line). [h] \centering [scale=1.2, >=stealth] \def unc(#1){0.5*(#1-2.5)*(#1-2.5) + 1} \def\zOne{0.8} \def\zTwo{4.2} \def\zMix{2.8} \pgfmathsetmacro{\yOne}{ unc(\zOne)} \pgfmathsetmacro{\yTwo}{ unc(\zTwo)} \pgfmathsetmacro{\yCurve}{ unc(\zMix)} \pgfmathsetmacro{\slope}{(\yTwo - \yOne) / (\zTwo - \zOne)} \pgfmathsetmacro{\yLine}{\yOne + \slope * (\zMix - \zOne)} \draw[->] (-0.5,0) -- (5.5,0) node[right] {$S$}; \draw[->] (0,-0.5) -- (0,5) node[above] {$f(S)$}; \draw[line width=1.2pt] plot[domain=0.2:4.8, samples=100] (\x, {0.5*(\x-2.5)*(\x-2.5) + 1}); \draw[red, line width=1.2pt] (\zOne, \yOne) -- (\zTwo, \yTwo);  illdraw (\zOne, \yOne) circle (1.5pt) node[above left, text=blue] {$f(z_1)$};  illdraw (\zTwo, \yTwo) circle (1.5pt) node[above left, text=teal] {$f(z_2)$};  illdraw (\zMix, \yCurve) circle (1.5pt);  illdraw (\zMix, \yLine) circle (1.5pt); \draw[dashed] (\zOne, 0) -- (\zOne, \yOne); \draw[dashed] (\zTwo, 0) -- (\zTwo, \yTwo); \draw[dashed] (\zMix, 0) -- (\zMix, \yCurve); \draw[dashed] (\zMix, \yCurve) -- (\zMix, \yLine); \draw[dashed] (0, \yCurve) -- (\zMix, \yCurve); \draw[dashed] (0, \yLine) -- (\zMix, \yLine); 
