ode[blue, font=	iny, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] at (axis cs: 3.2, 3.2) {$J=20$}; \draw[fill=teal, draw=black, thick] (axis cs:0,0) circle [radius=0.15]; 
ode[anchor=north west] at (axis cs:0.1, 0.6) {	iny min $(0,0)$}; \captionof{figure}{Level Curves of $J(x) = x_1^2 + x_2^2$.} The optimiser searches for the level curve with the smallest possible $c$. Geometrically, this is the centre of the concentric circles. Constrained Optimisation In most engineering applications, particularly MPC, we are restricted. Valves cannot open more than 100\%, and tanks cannot hold negative volume. This leads to constrained optimisation, where $x$ must belong to a specific feasible set $S$. We classify these based on how the set $S$ is defined. \paragraph{Type A: Equality Constraints} An equality constrained problem restricts the decision variables to lie strictly on a specific curve or surface ($h(x)=0$). The solver is not allowed to choose any point off this line. Mathematically, this reduces the dimension of the search space. {Equality Constraints: The Tangent Point} Problem Statement: Minimise the same quadratic function as before, but subject to a linear equality constraint. & \min_{x} \quad J(x) = x_1^2 + x_2^2 	ext{subject to:} & & h(x) = x_1 + 2x_2 - 4 = 0 Visualisation: This problem is visualised in Figure~. [scale=1.2] [ axis lines = middle, xlabel = $x_1$, ylabel = $x_2$, xmin = -1, xmax = 5, ymin = -1, ymax = 4, axis equal image, grid = major, ] \draw[blue, dashed] (axis cs:0,0) circle [radius=1]; \draw[blue, dashed] (axis cs:0,0) circle [radius=1.788]; \draw[blue, dashed] (axis cs:0,0) circle [radius=2.5]; \draw[blue, dashed] (axis cs:0,0) circle [radius=3.5]; \addplot[domain=-1:5, samples=2, color=red, ultra thick, dashed] {2 - 0.5*x}; 
