ode[anchor=south west] at (axis cs:0.85, 1.6) {Optimal $(0.8, 1.6)$}; \captionof{figure}{Minimising $J(x)$ on the line $h(x)=0$}. \solution The optimal point is found where the constraint line is exactly {tangent} to a level curve. \paragraph{Type B: Inequality Constraints} Unlike equality constraints, inequality constraints confine the solution to a region (a set of alternatives). The optimal solution may lie on the boundary of this region (active constraint) or strictly inside it (inactive constraint). {Inequality Constraints: The Feasible Region} Minimise the cost function $J(x) = x_1^2 + x_2^2$, subject to four linear inequalities: \[ -x_1 - 2x_2 + 5 &\leq 0 2x_1 + x_2 - 5 &\leq 0 x_1 \ge 0, \ x_2 &\ge 0 \] \solution Visualisation is excellent for understanding, but to get numerical answers, we use software. In this course, we utilise YALMIP, an open source MATLAB toolbox that allows us to write optimisation problems using syntax that looks almost identical to the mathematics. The workflow always follows three steps: Define Optimisation Variables $	o$ Define Model $	o$ Solve. [language=Matlab] x = sdpvar(2,1); J = x(1)^2 + x(2)^2; Constraints = [ -x(1) - 2*x(2) + 5 <= 0, ... 2*x(1) + x(2) - 5 <= 0, ... x(1) >= 0, ... x(2) >= 0 ]; optimize(Constraints, J); x_star = value(x) Visualisation: Geometrically, the optimiser ``expands'' the level curves (blue circles) from the origin until they first touch the feasible region (grey polygon). [scale=1.5] [ axis lines = middle, xlabel = $x_1$, ylabel = $x_2$, xmin = -1, xmax = 5, ymin = -1, ymax = 6, axis equal image, grid = major, ] \draw[blue, dashed] (axis cs:0,0) circle [radius=2.236]; \draw[blue, dashed] (axis cs:0,0) circle [radius=3.5]; \draw[blue, dashed] (axis cs:0,0) circle [radius=4.5]; 
