ode[anchor=north east] at (axis cs:1, 2) {{	iny Optimal $(1, 2)$}}; \paragraph{Type C: General Constraints} In the most general case, a problem contains both equality and inequality constraints. The solver must find a solution that lies inside the inequality region and lies exactly on the equality curve. Geometrically, the feasible set is the intersection of the regions defined by all constraints. This often effectively reduces the dimensionality of the search space. {General Constraints: Mixing Equalities and Inequalities} Problem Statement: Consider a scenario where we must satisfy both safety limits (inequalities) and strict physical laws (equalities). We wish to minimise the quadratic cost $J(x) = x_1^2 + x_2^2$ subject to: 	ext{s.t.} \quad & -x_1 - 2x_2 + 5 \leq 0 & 2x_1 + x_2 - 5 \leq 0 & x_1 \ge 0, \quad x_2 \ge 0 & x_1 + 2x_2 - 7 = 0 \quad {(Equality)} \solution YALMIP Implementation: When translating this into code, pay close attention to the syntax for the equality constraint. In MATLAB, a single equals sign (=) represents assignment (e.g., setting a variable's value). To represent a logical equality condition ($h(x)=0$), we must use the double equals sign (==). [language=Matlab] x = sdpvar(2,1); J = x(1)^2 + x(2)^2; g1 = [-x(1) - 2*x(2) + 5 <= 0]; g2 = [ 2*x(1) + x(2) - 5 <= 0]; g3 = [x(1) >= 0]; g4 = [x(2) >= 0]; h = [x(1) + 2*x(2) - 7 == 0]; Constraints = [g1, g2, g3, g4, h]; optimize(Constraints, J); x_star = value(x) Visualisation and Analysis: The geometry of this problem is illustrated in Figure~. \item The inequalities form the grey triangular region. \item The equality constraint is represented by the orange dashed line. A valid solution must satisfy both conditions. Therefore, the feasible set is reduced to the specific line segment where the orange line slices through the grey triangle. [scale=1.2] [ axis lines = middle, xlabel = $x_1$, ylabel = $x_2$, xmin = -4, xmax = 5, ymin = -2, ymax = 6, axis equal image, grid = major, ] \draw[blue, dashed] (axis cs:0,0) circle [radius=2.236]; \draw[blue, dashed] (axis cs:0,0) circle [radius=3.162]; \draw[blue, dashed] (axis cs:0,0) circle [radius=4.5]; \draw[blue, dashed] (axis cs:0,0) circle [radius=1];  ill[gray, opacity=0.3] (axis cs:0, 2.5) -- (axis cs:0, 5) -- (axis cs:1.666, 1.666) -- cycle; \addplot[domain=-0.5:5, color=orange, ultra thick, dashed] {3.5 - 0.5*x}; 
ode[red, font=
ormalsize, rotate=-26, anchor=south] at (axis cs: 3, 1.9) { $x_1 + 2x_2 = 7$};  ill[gray, draw=black] (axis cs:1, 2) circle (2pt); 
ode[darkgray, font=\scriptsize, anchor=north east] at (axis cs:1, 2) {Old Optimum $(1, 2)$};  ill[teal, draw=black, thick] (axis cs:1, 3) circle (3pt); 
ode[anchor=south west, font=\scriptsize] at (axis cs:1, 3) { New Optimum $(1, 3)$}; \captionof{figure}{Intersection of Equality and Inequalities} The Cost of Constraints: In the previous example (inequalities only), the optimiser could reach the point $(1,2)$, which yielded a cost of $J=5$. However, the new equality constraint forces the solution to lie on the line $x_1 + 2x_2 = 7$. The point $(1,2)$ is no longer valid because $1 + 2(2) = 5 
eq 7$. The solver is forced to move further away from the origin to satisfy this new rule, settling at $(1,3)$ with a higher cost of $J=10$. This illustrates a fundamental rule of engineering optimisation: {Adding constraints generally worsens (increases) the minimum cost}, as it restricts the freedom of the solver to find "cheaper" solutions.

Optimisation problems vary greatly in difficulty depending on the structure of their objective functions and constraints. In this section we review some of the most commonly encountered problem classes, beginning with those that are considered easy from a computational point of view, and progressing to problems that are, in general, far more challenging to solve. Linear Programmes (LPs) Linear Programmes constitute one of the most fundamental classes of convex optimisation problems. Both the objective and the constraints are linear: &\min_{x} \; c^{	op} x 	ext{subject to: } & &Gx \le h &Ax = b The feasible set of an LP is a polyhedron, and the optimum, when it exists, is attained at an extreme point (vertex) of this polyhedron. Linear optimisation on a polytope may be visualised as shifting parallel hyperplanes of constant cost until they touch the feasible region. Figure~ shows a 2D example where the polytope corresponds to the closed area modelled by $Gx\le h$ and dashed lines shows the cost for different values of $c^	op x$. [!htb] \centering [scale=2] \coordinate (A) at (0.5, 0); \coordinate (B) at (0, 0.8); \coordinate (C) at (0.8, 1.5); \coordinate (D) at (2, 1.3); \coordinate (E) at (2.2, 0.5);  ill[gray!40] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- (E) -- cycle; \draw[line width=1.2pt] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- (E) -- cycle;  oreach \y in {-0.3, 0.3, 0.9, 1.5, 2.1, 2.7} { \draw[dashed, gray, rotate = -36, thick] (-0.5, \y) -- (3, \y); } 
ode at (1.1, 0.9) { $Gx \le h$}; 
ode[circle, fill=black, inner sep=2pt] at (A) {}; 
ode[below right] at (A) {$x^*$}; \caption{Linear optimisation on a polytope.} {Linear Programme: Minimum-Effort Steady State} The Goal: Consider a discrete-time linear system $$x_{k+1} = Ax_k + Bu_k$$ We wish to find a steady-state pair $(x_{\mathrm{ss}}, u_{\mathrm{ss}})$ (an equilibrium point where the system stays at rest ($x_{k+1} = x_k$)) subject to safety constraints. Crucially, among all possible valid equilibria, we want to find the one that requires the least control effort. In engineering (e.g., satellite thrusters), "effort" is often quantified by fuel consumption, which corresponds to the sum of the absolute values of the inputs. 1. The 1-Norm and Notation: Mathematically, we want to minimise the 1-norm of the input vector $u \in \mathbb{R}^m$: \|u\|_1 = \sum_{i=1}^{m} |u_i| = |u_1|+|u_2|+\cdots + |u_m| However, the absolute value function $|u|$ is non-linear. Standard LP solvers cannot handle it directly. To solve this, we use a standard optimisation trick involving the vector $1$. \item Let $1$ be a column vector of ones: $1 = [1, 1, \dots, 1]^	op$. \item Then $1^	op t$ is simply the sum of the elements of vector $t$: $\sum t_i$. 2. The Epigraph Trick: We introduce an auxiliary decision vector $t \in \mathbb{R}^m$. We constrain $t$ to be an upper bound on the magnitude of $u$: -t_i \le u_i \le t_i \implies |u_i| \le t_i If we minimise the sum of elements in $t$ (i.e., $\min 1^	op t$), the solver will squeeze $t_i$ down until $t_i = |u_i|$. This effectively minimises $|u_i|$ using only linear inequalities. 3. The Formulation: We can now pose the full Linear Programme. The decision variables are the input $u$, the state $x_{\mathrm{ss}}$, and the auxiliary bound $t$. \[ &\min_{u,\, x_{\mathrm{ss}},\, t} \quad 1^	op t && 	ext{(Minimise total fuel/effort)} 	ext{subject to:} &&& & (I-A)x_{\mathrm{ss}} - Bu = 0, && 	ext{(Equilibrium Physics)} & G\,x_{\mathrm{ss}} \le h, && 	ext{(Safety Constraints)} & u_{\min} \le u \le u_{\max}, && 	ext{(Actuator Limits)} & -t \le u \le t. && 	ext{(Norm Linearisation)} \] This formulation allows us to find the most efficient operating point for the system using extremely fast and reliable Linear Programming solvers. {Stigler's Diet Problem:} The Stigler Diet Problem is a classic linear optimisation problem. The objective is to determine the most cost-effective daily diet that meets specific nutritional requirements using a limited set of foods. In this simplified 2D version, we consider two food items: {Corn} and {Wheat Bread}. We aim to minimise the total daily cost while satisfying constraints for {Energy (Calories)} and {Vitamin A}. We first define the problem using general parameters and units. Decision Variables: \item $x_1$: Quantity of Corn [kg] \item $x_2$: Quantity of Bread [kg] Parameters: \item $c_1, c_2$: Price of food [\$/kg] \item $k_1, k_2$: Energy content [kcal/kg] \item $v_1, v_2$: Vitamin A content [$\mu$g/kg] \item $K_{min}, K_{max}$: Daily energy limits [kcal] \item $V_{min}, V_{max}$: Daily Vitamin A limits [$\mu$g] Optimisation Model: \underset{x_1,\,x_2}{	ext{min}} \quad & J(x) = c_1 x_1 + c_2 x_2 	ext {Subject to:} \quad & K_{min} \leq k_1 x_1 + k_2 x_2 \leq K_{max} & V_{min} \leq v_1 x_1 + v_2 x_2 \leq V_{max} & x_1 \geq 0, \quad x_2 \geq 0 Using the specific data provided for the problem: Data: \item Costs: $c_1 = 2.0$, $c_2 = 0.5$ \item Energy: $k_1 = 750$, $k_2 = 650$ (Target: $2000 - 3000$ kcal) \item Vitamin A: $v_1 = 250$, $v_2 = 0$ (Target: $500 - 800$ $\mu$g) Numerically, the problem can be stated as follows: &\underset{x_1,x_2}{\min } \quad J(x) = 2x_1 + 0.5x_2 & 	ext{Subject to:} && &2000 \leq 750x_1 + 650x_2 \leq 3000 & 	ext{(Energy)} &500 \leq 250x_1 \phantom{{} + 650x_2} \leq 800 & 	ext{(Vitamin A)} & x_1 \geq 0, \quad x_2 \geq 0 & 	ext{(Nonnegativity)} Figure~ shows the feasible solution set along with the optimal solution that minimises the cost of nutrition. [language=Matlab, caption=Solving Stigler's Problem with YALMIP] clear; clc; x1 = sdpvar(1); x2 = sdpvar(1); Objective = 2*x1 + 0.5*x2; Constraints = []; Constraints = [Constraints, 2000 <= 750*x1 + 650*x2 <= 3000]; Constraints = [Constraints, 500 <= 250*x1 <= 800]; Constraints = [Constraints, x1 >= 0, x2 >= 0]; options = sdpsettings('verbose', 0, 'solver', 'linprog'); sol = optimize(Constraints, Objective, options); if sol.problem == 0 fprintf('Optimal Solution:
'); fprintf('x1 (Corn) : fprintf('x2 (Bread): fprintf('Min Cost : $ else disp('Problem could not be solved.'); end [h!] \centering \includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{Figures/Stigler2d} \caption{Numerical solution of the 2d Stigler problem in MATLAB.} Convex Quadratic Programmes (QPs) Quadratic Programmes (QPs) extend linear optimisation by allowing a quadratic objective function whilst retaining linear equality and inequality constraints. A QP takes the general form &\min_{x} \quad  rac{1}{2} x^{	op} P x + q^{	op} x 	ext{subject to: } & & Gx \le h & Ax = b where, $x\in \mathbb R^n$, $P \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes n}$, $q \in \mathbb{R}^n$, $G \in \mathbb{R}^{m 	imes n}$, and $A \in \mathbb{R}^{p 	imes n}$. The feasible region defined by the linear constraints is always a polyhedron. The QP is convex if and only if the Hessian matrix $P$ is positive semidefinite: \[ P \succeq 0 . \] This is shown in Figure~. {Tests for Positive Semidefiniteness ($P \succeq 0$)} For a symmetric matrix \(P\), the following statements are equivalent and may be used to verify that \(P\) is positive semidefinite: \item Eigenvalues: All eigenvalues of \(P\) are non-negative: \[ \lambda_i(P) \ge 0, \qquad i=1,\dots,n. \] \item Quadratic Form: The quadratic form is non-negative for every vector \(z \in \mathbb{R}^n\): \[ z^	op P z \ge 0, \qquad  orall z \in \mathbb{R}^n. \] \item Principal Minors: All principal minors of \(P\) are non-negative. In other words, the determinant of every principal submatrix must satisfy \[ \det(P_{\mathcal I,\mathcal I}) \ge 0 \] for every index set \(\mathcal I \subseteq \{1,\dots,n\}\). Important note: For positive definite matrices \((P \succ 0)\), Sylvester's criterion states that it is enough to check that all leading principal minors are strictly positive. However, for positive semidefinite matrices \((P \succeq 0)\), checking only the leading principal minors is not sufficient in general; one must check all principal minors, or use one of the equivalent tests above. (For a review of eigenvalues, definiteness, and related matrix concepts, see Appendix~.) {Hessian} The Hessian matrix, denoted as $
abla^2 f(x)$ or $H(x)$, collects all second-order partial derivatives of a scalar-valued function $f: \mathbb{R}^n 	o \mathbb{R}$. If $x = [x_1, x_2, \dots, x_n]^	op$, the element in the $i$-th row and $j$-th column is given by: H_{ij} = \dfrac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_i \partial x_j} {Example: Hessian} Consider a simple function of two variables: \[ f(x) = 3x_1^2 + 2x_1 x_2 + 5x_2^2 \] First, we find the gradient (first derivatives): \[ \dfrac{\partial f}{\partial x_1} = 6x_1 + 2x_2, \quad \dfrac{\partial f}{\partial x_2} = 2x_1 + 10x_2 \] Differentiating again gives the Hessian matrix: \[ H = \dfrac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_1^2} & \dfrac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_1 \partial x_2} [12pt] \dfrac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_2 \partial x_1} & \dfrac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_2^2} = 6 & 2 2 & 10 \] Note that for smooth functions, the Hessian is always a symmetric matrix ($H_{ij} = H_{ji}$). In the strictly convex case (where $P \succ 0$), the level sets of the objective function form concentric ellipses. This structure guarantees that the optimisation problem yields a unique global minimiser, provided the feasible region is non-empty. Geometrically, the solver searches for the smallest possible ellipse that still overlaps with the constraints. The optimal solution is found at the precise point where this lowest-cost contour touches (or grazes) the feasible polytope. This graphical interpretation is illustrated in Figure~. [!h] \centering [scale=1.5]  ill[gray!30] (0,0) -- (1.4,0.2) -- (1.9,1.4) -- (1.0,2.2) -- (-0.4,1.4) -- cycle; \draw[black, thick] (0,0) -- (1.4,0.2) -- (1.9,1.4) -- (1.0,2.2) -- (-0.4,1.4) -- cycle;  oreach \scale in {0.6,1.2,1.8,3,4,6} { \draw[dashed, domain=0:360] plot ({2.55 + 0.45*\scale*cos(\x)}, {0.9 + 0.25*\scale*sin(\x)}); }  illdraw[black] (1.65,0.9) circle (2pt); 
ode at (1.38,0.65) {$x^\star$}; 
ode at (0.4,1.2) {$P$}; \caption{Convex quadratic optimisation on a polytope. Contours indicate decreasing objective value towards the optimal point $x^\star$.} Convex QPs benefit from strong theoretical guarantees and can be solved efficiently using interior-point, active-set, or first-order optimisation methods. They are widely used in control, signal processing, finance, estimation, and engineering design. {Example: Robot Distance to a Restricted Zone} Scenario: Let a robot is located at coordinates $p = (3, 2)$. A restricted geometric zone $\mathcal{X}$ (representing an obstacle or a target landing pad) is defined as a unit box centered at the origin. The robot must compute the shortest distance to this zone to plan its trajectory. \solution Optimisation Problem: Find the point $x \in \mathcal{X}$ closest to $p$: \min_{x \in \mathbb{R}^2} \; (x_1 - 3)^2 + (x_2 - 2)^2 Constraints (Standard Format): The unit box is defined by bounds $-1 \leq x_1 \leq 1$ and $-1 \leq x_2 \leq 1$. In standard linear inequality form $Ax \leq b$, these are written as: x_1 &\leq 1 -x_1 &\leq 1 x_2 &\leq 1 -x_2 &\leq 1 Visualising the Solution: By inspecting the geometry (see Figure ), the closest point within the box to $(3,2)$ is the upper-right corner of the box, $x^* = (1, 1)$. [scale=1.5, >=stealth]  illdraw[fill=blue!20, draw=blue!80!black, thick] (-1, -1) rectangle (1, 1); 
ode[blue!80!black] at (0.3, -0.3) {$\mathcal{X}$}; \coordinate (P) at (3, 2);  illdraw[black] (P) circle (2pt) node[above right] {$p = (3, 2)$}; \coordinate (Sol) at (1, 1);  illdraw[red] (Sol) circle (2pt) node[below right, yshift=-5pt] {$x^* = (1, 1)$}; \draw[red, dashed, thick] (P) -- (Sol) node[midway, above left, text=black] {min dist}; \draw[dotted] (3, 0) node[below] {$3$} -- (P); \draw[dotted] (0, 2) node[left] {$2$} -- (P); \draw[dotted] (1, 0) node[below, xshift=-5pt] {$1$} -- (1, -1); \draw[dotted] (0, 1) node[left, yshift=-5pt] {$1$} -- (-1, 1); \draw[->] (-2, 0) -- (4.5, 0) node[right] {$x_1$}; \draw[->] (0, -2) -- (0, 3) node[above] {$x_2$}; \captionof{figure}{Geometry of the optimisation problem.} To solve this problem numerically using a solver (like OSQP, quadprog, or GUROBI), we must map the problem into the standard Quadratic Programming form: \min_{x} \;  rac{1}{2} x^	op P x + q^	op x \quad 	ext{subject to} \quad Gx \leq h We expand the squared Euclidean distance objective: J(x) &= (x_1 - 3)^2 + (x_2 - 2)^2 &= (x_1^2 - 6x_1 + 9) + (x_2^2 - 4x_2 + 4) &= \underbrace{x_1^2 + x_2^2}_{	ext{Quadratic part}} \underbrace{- 6x_1 - 4x_2}_{	ext{Linear part}} + \underbrace{13}_{	ext{Constant}} The constant term ($13$) does not affect the optimal location $x^*$ and is discarded. To match the standard form $ rac{1}{2} x^	op P x$, the matrix $P$ must be scaled such that the diagonal elements are 2. \[  rac{1}{2} \underbrace{ x_1 & x_2 }_{x^	op} \underbrace{ 2 & 0 0 & 2 }_{P} \underbrace{ x_1 x_2 }_{x} + \underbrace{ -6 & -4 }_{q^	op} x_1 x_2 \] Thus, we define: \[ P = 2 & 0 0 & 2 , \quad q = -6 -4 \] The unit box constraints are: \[ -1 \leq x_1 \leq 1 \quad 	ext{and} \quad -1 \leq x_2 \leq 1 \] These must be rewritten as "less than or equal to" inequalities ($Gx \leq h$): x_1 &\leq 1 -x_1 &\leq 1 x_2 &\leq 1 -x_2 &\leq 1 In matrix notation, this becomes: \[ \underbrace{ 1 & 0 -1 & 0 0 & 1 0 & -1 }_{G} x_1 x_2 \leq \underbrace{ 1 1 1 1 }_{h} \] \subsection*{MATLAB Implementation using YALMIP} Having derived the standard QP matrices manually, we can now solve the problem using MATLAB. The following code demonstrates YALMIP's symbolic framework to automate the process. [caption={Solving the Robot Trajectory QP using YALMIP and quadprog.}, label={lst:yalmip_qp}] clear; clc; ops = sdpsettings('solver', 'quadprog', 'verbose', 0); p = [3; 2]; x = sdpvar(2, 1); Objective = (x(1) - p(1))^2 + (x(2) - p(2))^2; Constraints = [-1 <= x <= 1]; optimize(Constraints , Objective, ops); x_opt = value(x); fprintf('Optimal Sol : x1= \subsection*{Direct Implementation using quadprog} While YALMIP offers a convenient high-level interface, it is essential to understand how to pass the problem matrices directly to a solver. This effectively opens the "black box" of the optimisation tool. In MATLAB, the native solver quadprog ootnote{requires optimization toolbox} solves problems of the form: \min_x  rac{1}{2}x^	op H x + f^	op x \quad 	ext{subject to} \quad A x \leq b This syntax requires a direct mapping from our mathematical notation ($P, q, G, h$) to MATLAB's standard arguments ($H, f, A, b$). [caption={Direct solution using MATLAB's built-in quadprog solver.}, label={lst:quadprog_direct}] clear; clc; H = [2, 0; 0, 2]; f = [-6; -4]; A = [ 1, 0; -1, 0; 0, 1; 0, -1]; b = [1; 1; 1; 1]; options = optimoptions('quadprog', 'Display', 'off'); x_opt = quadprog(H, f, A, b, [], [], [], [], [], options); fprintf('Optimal Sol : x1= Nonconvex Quadratic Programmes Not all optimisation problems retain convexity. Once convexity is lost, global optimality becomes substantially harder to guarantee. While standard MPC relies on convex optimisation, certain control formulations lead to nonconvex problems. A specific class of these "hard" problems is the Nonconvex Quadratic Programme (QP). When the matrix $P$ in the quadratic objective is not positive semidefinite ($P 
