nergy (kWh)}, u(k) &\in \{0,1\} && 	ext{generator on/off status}, s(k) &\in \{0,1\} && 	ext{generator start-up indicator}, z(k) &\in \{0,1\} && 	ext{battery charge mode indicator}. \medskip Objective function: The total operating cost is given by \min \sum_{k=1}^{N} \Delta t \left( c_{\mathrm{grid}}(k)\,p_{\mathrm{grid}}(k) + c_f\,p_g(k) ight) + \sum_{k=1}^{N} c_{\mathrm{start}}\, s(k), where $c_{\mathrm{grid}}(k)$ denotes the time-varying electricity price, $c_f$ the generator fuel cost coefficient, and $c_{\mathrm{start}}$ the generator start-up cost. \medskip Constraints: Power balance: p_{\mathrm{grid}}(k) + p_g(k) + p_{\mathrm{dis}}(k) - p_{\mathrm{ch}}(k) = d(k), \quad  orall k. The term $d(k)$ represents the exogenous electrical demand (load) of the system at time step $k$, assumed to be known over the prediction horizon. Generator operating limits: P_{g,\min} u(k) \le p_g(k) \le P_{g,\max} u(k), \quad  orall k. Generator start-up logic: s(1) &\ge u(1), s(k) &\ge u(k) - u(k-1), \quad k=2,\dots,N. where $s(k)$ is a binary variable that equals one if the generator is started at time $k$, i.e. when the on/off status $u(k)$ transitions from 0 to 1. Battery energy dynamics: E(k+1) = E(k) + \Delta t\,\eta_{\mathrm{ch}}\,p_{\mathrm{ch}}(k) - \Delta t\, rac{1}{\eta_{\mathrm{dis}}}\,p_{\mathrm{dis}}(k), with $E(1)=E_0$. Also, $\eta_{\mathrm{ch}}\in(0,1]$ and $\eta_{\mathrm{dis}}\in(0,1]$ denote the charging and discharging efficiencies of the battery, respectively. Battery and grid limits: E_{\min} &\le E(k) \le E_{\max}, 0 &\le p_{\mathrm{ch}}(k) \le P_{\mathrm{ch},\max}, 0 &\le p_{\mathrm{dis}}(k) \le P_{\mathrm{dis},\max}, 0 &\le p_{\mathrm{grid}}(k) \le P_{\mathrm{grid},\max}. Nonsimultaneous charging and discharging: p_{\mathrm{ch}}(k) &\le P_{\mathrm{ch},\max} z(k), p_{\mathrm{dis}}(k) &\le P_{\mathrm{dis},\max} [1-z(k)]. 	cbline Solving this problem: The model above is a Mixed-Integer Linear Programme (MILP) due to the binary variables $u(k), s(k), z(k)$. It r