{Newton--Raphson Iteration} We seek $x^*$ such that $g(x^*)=0$, but we cannot solve this equation directly. Instead, we approximate $g$ near the current iterate $x_k$ using a first-order Taylor expansion: \[ g(x) \;\approx\; g(x_k) + g'(x_k)\,(x - x_k). \] Setting this linear approximation to zero and solving for $x$ gives the next iterate: \[ 0 = g(x_k) + g'(x_k)\,(x_{k+1} - x_k) \quad\Longrightarrow\quad {\;x_{k+1} \;=\; x_k \;-\;  rac{g(x_k)}{g'(x_k)}\;} \] Geometrically, this replaces the curve $g$ by its tangent line at $x_k$ and takes the root of that tangent as the next iterate. The process repeats, producing progressively better approximations. Convergence is quadratic near the root: there exists a constant $C>0$ such that \[ |x_{k+1}-x^*| \;\le\; C\,|x_k-x^*|^2. \] This means the number of correct digits roughly doubles at each step. [scale=1.3, >=stealth] \draw[->] (-0.5,0) -- (4.5,0) node[right] {$x$}; \draw[->] (0,-1.5) -- (0,3.0) node[above] {$g(x)$}; \draw[thick, blue!80!black, domain=0:4.2, samples=80, smooth] plot (\x, {3*(\x/6)^2 - 6*(\x/6) + 2});  ill[teal] (2.536, 0) circle (2.5pt); 
