The unconstrained methods we have studied so far find minima by solving $
abla J(x^*) = 0$. However, in Model Predictive Control, we always operate under constraints---dynamics equations impose equality constraints, while actuator limits and safety bounds impose inequalities. How do we find a minimum when the optimum is forced to lie on a constraint surface? Geometric Intuition: Tangency of Level Curves Consider minimising $J(x) = x_1^2 + x_2^2$ subject to $x_1 + 2x_2 = 4$. The level curves of $J$ are concentric circles centred at the origin. The constraint is a straight line. As we move along the constraint line, $J$ decreases until we reach a point where the constraint is tangent to a level curve---this is the constrained minimum. At this special point, the gradient of $J$ is parallel to the gradient of the constraint: \[ 
abla J(x^*) = -\lambda \,
abla h(x^*) \quad 	ext{for some scalar } \lambda. \] The key geometric insight is that if $
abla J$ had any component along the constraint surface, we could slide along the constraint and further reduce $J$. Only when the gradient of $J$ is entirely perpendicular to the constraint (i.e., parallel to $
abla h$) is there no improving direction remaining. [scale=1.1, >=stealth] \draw[->] (-0.5,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {$x_1$}; \draw[->] (0,-0.5) -- (0,4.5) node[above] {$x_2$};  oreach /\lab in {1/{J=1}, 2/{J=4}, 3/{J=9}, 4/{J=16}} { \draw[blue!50, dashed] (0,0) circle (); } 
