The KKT conditions tell us what the optimal solution looks like. But how do practical QP solvers---the workhorses behind every MPC controller---actually find that solution? Two dominant algorithmic paradigms exist: the active-set method and the interior-point method. Understanding their mechanics helps MPC engineers choose the right solver, diagnose convergence failures, and exploit warm-starting. The Active-Set Method The active-set method is motivated by a simple observation: if we knew which inequality constraints were active (binding) at the optimum, we could replace them with equalities and solve an equality-constrained QP---a problem that reduces to a single linear system. Of course, we do not know the active set in advance, so the algorithm discovers it iteratively. The method maintains a working set $\mathcal{W}_k$: the subset of inequality constraints currently treated as equalities. At each iteration, the algorithm performs the following steps: \item Solve the equality-constrained subproblem. With the constraints in $\mathcal{W}_k$ enforced as equalities (and all other inequality constraints temporarily ignored), solve the resulting KKT system to obtain a candidate step $d_k$ and the associated Lagrange multipliers $\mu_i$ for $i \in \mathcal{W}_k$. \item If $d_k = 0$ (no improving direction exists within the working set): \item Check the multipliers. If $\mu_i \geq 0$ for all $i \in \mathcal{W}_k$, the KKT conditions are satisfied---stop, we are optimal. \item If some $\mu_j < 0$, then constraint $j$ was incorrectly assumed active. Remove it from $\mathcal{W}_k$ and repeat. \item If $d_k 
eq 0$ (an improving direction exists): \item Take a step along $d_k$, using the largest step length $\alpha_k \in (0, 1]$ that does not violate any inactive constraint. \item If an inactive constraint becomes active (a blocking constraint), add it to $\mathcal{W}_k$. \item Update the iterate: $x_{k+1} = x_k + \alpha_k d_k$. Geometrically, the method walks along edges and vertices of the feasible polytope, much like the simplex method for linear programmes. Each iteration either moves to a new vertex (adding or dropping a constraint from the working set) or confirms optimality. For convex QPs, the algorithm terminates in a finite number of iterations---bounded by $ inom{m}{n}$ working-set combinations in the worst case, but typically far fewer in practice. [>=stealth, scale=1.4] \coordinate (V1) at (0, 0); \coordinate (V2) at (3.5, 0); \coordinate (V3) at (4, 2.5); \coordinate (V4) at (1.5, 3.5); \coordinate (V5) at (0, 2);  ill[gray!15] (V1) -- (V2) -- (V3) -- (V4) -- (V5) -- cycle; \draw[thick, black] (V1) -- (V2) -- (V3) -- (V4) -- (V5) -- cycle; \coordinate (unc) at (3.0, 3.5); \draw[blue!50, dashed, thick] (unc) ellipse (0.4 and 0.3); \draw[blue!40, dashed] (unc) ellipse (0.9 and 0.65); \draw[blue!30, dashed] (unc) ellipse (1.5 and 1.1); \draw[blue!20, dashed] (unc) ellipse (2.2 and 1.6); \draw[blue!60, thick] (unc) circle (3pt); 
