ode[blue!60, right] at (3.6, 3.5) { ootnotesize $J(x) = 	ext{const}$}; \captionof{figure}{Active-set method for a QP: the algorithm walks along edges and vertices of the feasible polytope, adjusting the working set at each step until the KKT conditions are satisfied.} {Warm-Starting in MPC} Between consecutive MPC time steps, the optimal solution shifts only slightly (the system has moved by one time step). The active set from the previous solution is almost always correct for the new problem. Solvers like qpOASES exploit this by warm-starting: initialising the working set from the previous solution, so that only 1--3 iterations are needed to solve the new QP. This is what makes active-set methods the preferred choice for real-time linear MPC, achieving solve times well below 1\,ms for moderate problem sizes. The Interior-Point (Barrier) Method The interior-point method takes a contrasting philosophy to the active-set approach: instead of walking along the boundary of the feasible region, it approaches the optimum from the interior. The key idea is to replace the hard inequality constraints $g_i(x) \leq 0$ with a smooth penalty that becomes infinite at the boundary, keeping all iterates strictly inside the feasible region. Concretely, the inequality-constrained problem is approximated by the barrier problem: \min_{x} \; J(x) - t \sum_{i=1}^{m} \ln igl(-g_i(x) igr), where $t > 0$ is the barrier parameter. The logarithmic term $-t \ln(-g_i(x))$ is finite only when $g_i(x) < 0$ (strictly feasible) and blows up to $+\infty$ as $g_i(x) 	o 0^-$, creating an invisible repulsive wall at each constraint boundary. For each fixed $t > 0$, the barrier problem~ is an unconstrained (or equality-constrained) smooth problem that can be solved by Newton's method. The solution $x^*(t)$ lies in the strict interior of the feasible set. As $t 	o 0$, the barrier penalty weakens and $x^*(t)$ approaches the true constrained optimum $x^*$. The curve traced by $x^*(t)$ as $t$ decreases is called the central path. A crucial advantage of interior-point methods is their worst-case complexity: $O(\sqrt{m} \cdot \log(1/\varepsilon))$ Newton steps suffice to reach $\varepsilon$-optimality, where $m$ is the number of inequality constraints. This polynomial-time guarantee contrasts with the potentially exponential worst case of active-set methods (though active-set methods are typically faster in practice for small, warm-started problems). [>=stealth, scale=1.4] \coordinate (V1) at (0, 0); \coordinate (V2) at (3.5, 0); \coordinate (V3) at (4, 2.5); \coordinate (V4) at (1.5, 3.5); \coordinate (V5) at (0, 2);  ill[gray!15] (V1) -- (V2) -- (V3) -- (V4) -- (V5) -- cycle; \draw[thick, black] (V1) -- (V2) -- (V3) -- (V4) -- (V5) -- cycle; \coordinate (P0) at (0, 0); \coordinate (P1) at (3.5, 0); \coordinate (P2) at (4, 2.5); \coordinate (P3) at (2.8, 2.98); \draw[->, gray!40, thick] (P0) -- (P1); \draw[->, gray!40, thick] (P1) -- (P2); \draw[->, gray!40, thick] (P2) -- (P3);  ill[gray!50] (P0) circle (1.8pt);  ill[gray!50] (P1) circle (1.8pt);  ill[gray!50] (P2) circle (1.8pt);  ill[gray!50] (P3) circle (1.8pt); 
