\mu_i g_i(x) = 0$ to the perturbed form $\mu_i s_i = 	au$, where $	au > 0$ is the barrier parameter. The complete perturbed KKT system is: 
abla J(x) + \sum_{i=1}^{m} \mu_i 
abla g_i(x) + \sum_{j=1}^{q} \lambda_j 
abla h_j(x) &= 0, & & 	ext{(Stationarity)} h_j(x) &= 0, \quad j = 1,\ldots,q, & & 	ext{(Equality feasibility)} g_i(x) + s_i &= 0, \quad s_i > 0, \quad i = 1,\ldots,m, & & 	ext{(Slack definition)} S \mu &= 	au \mathbf{1}, & & 	ext{(Perturbed complementarity)} where $S = \operatorname{diag}(s_1, \ldots, s_m)$, $\mu = (\mu_1,\ldots,\mu_m)^	op$, and $\mathbf{1}$ is the vector of all ones. {Primal-Dual Interior-Point Method} Given the perturbed KKT system~, the primal-dual method proceeds as follows: \item Linearise: Compute the Newton step $(\Delta x, \Delta s, \Delta \mu, \Delta \lambda)$ by linearising system~ around the current iterate $(x_k, s_k, \mu_k, \lambda_k)$. \item Step length: Choose $\alpha \in (0, 1]$ to maintain strict positivity: $s_k + \alpha \Delta s > 0$ and $\mu_k + \alpha \Delta \mu > 0$. \item Update: Set $(x_{k+1}, s_{k+1}, \mu_{k+1}, \lambda_{k+1}) = (x_k, s_k, \mu_k, \lambda_k) + \alpha (\Delta x, \Delta s, \Delta \mu, \Delta \lambda)$. \item Reduce barrier: Update $	au \leftarrow \sigma 	au$ with centering parameter $\sigma \in (0, 1)$. \item Repeat until $	au < \varepsilon$ and the KKT residual is sufficiently small. The key advantage over the basic barrier method is efficiency: each iteration requires only one Newton step on the full KKT system, rather than an entire sub-problem solve. Moreover, the Newton system possesses a structured sparsity pattern that can be exploited via block elimination (the Schur complement), reducing the per-iteration linear algebra cost dramatically. Convergence is superlinear near the solution, meaning the method takes fewer total iterations than the basic barrier approach. {Why Primal-Dual Dominates Modern Solvers} The primal-dual interior-point method is the algorithm of choice for large-scale optimisation because: \item It requires $O(\sqrt{m}\, \log(1/\varepsilon))$ iterations regardless of the number of variables---each iteration is one Newton step on the KKT system. \item It naturally produces both primal ($x$) and dual ($\mu$, $\lambda$) solutions, providing sensitivity information for free. \item For QPs, the Newton system is a structured linear system with known sparsity, making each iteration very efficient to solve. [>=stealth, scale=1.4] \coordinate (V1) at (0, 0); \coordinate (V2) at (3.5, 0); \coordinate (V3) at (4, 2.5); \coordinate (V4) at (1.5, 3.5); \coordinate (V5) at (0, 2);  ill[gray!15] (V1) -- (V2) -- (V3) -- (V4) -- (V5) -- cycle; \draw[thick, black] (V1) -- (V2) -- (V3) -- (V4) -- (V5) -- cycle; \draw[teal!50, thick, smooth, tension=0.7] plot coordinates {(1.8, 1.2) (1.95, 1.4) (2.1, 1.6) (2.2, 1.75) (2.3, 1.9) (2.38, 2.05) (2.45, 2.18) (2.52, 2.3) (2.58, 2.42) (2.63, 2.52) (2.67, 2.62) (2.71, 2.7) (2.74, 2.78) (2.77, 2.88) (2.8, 2.98)};  oreach \px/\py in {1.8/1.2, 1.95/1.4, 2.1/1.6, 2.2/1.75, 2.3/1.9, 2.38/2.05, 2.45/2.18, 2.52/2.3, 2.58/2.42, 2.63/2.52, 2.67/2.62, 2.71/2.7, 2.74/2.78, 2.77/2.88} {  ill[teal!60] (\px, \py) circle (1.2pt); } \coordinate (PD0) at (1.8, 1.2); \coordinate (PD1) at (2.4, 2.15); \coordinate (PD2) at (2.65, 2.7); \coordinate (PD3) at (2.8, 2.98); \draw[->, teal, very thick] (PD0) -- (PD1); \draw[->, teal, very thick] (PD1) -- (PD2); \draw[->, teal, very thick] (PD2) -- (PD3);  ill[teal] (PD0) circle (3pt);  ill[teal] (PD1) circle (3pt);  ill[teal] (PD2) circle (3pt);  ill[teal] (PD3) circle (3pt); \draw[teal, thick] (PD3) circle (4pt); 
