ode[shape=rectangle, minimum width=1.465cm, minimum height=0.465cm] at (8.5, 9.5){} node[anchor=north west, align=left, text width=1.077cm, inner sep=6pt] at (7.75, 9.75){$v_C$}; \captionof{figure}{An RLC circuit.} \medskip \solution We select the energy variables as state variables: \[ x_1 = i_L \quad 	ext{(inductor current)}, \qquad x_2 = v_C \quad 	ext{(capacitor voltage)}, \] and take the input as \[ u = v_i . \] We begin with the constitutive relations of the energy–storage elements. Since the state variables are chosen as the inductor current and the capacitor voltage, all other variables are expressed in terms of these states and the input. v_L &= L  rac{d i_L}{dt}, i_C &= C  rac{d v_C}{dt}. The current flowing through resistor $R_2$ is given by Ohm’s law as \[ i_{R_2} =  rac{v_L - v_C}{R_2}. \] Applying Kirchhoff’s Current Law (KCL) at node $v_C$ and noting that the capacitor current equals the current through $R_2$ yields \[ C \dot{v}_C =  rac{v_L - v_C}{R_2}. \] Applying KCL at node $v_L$ yields \[  rac{v_i - v_L}{R_1} = i_L +  rac{v_L - v_C}{R_2}. \] Solving for $v_L$: \[ v_L =  rac{R_2}{R_1 + R_2} v_i -  rac{R_1 R_2}{R_1 + R_2} i_L +  rac{R_1}{R_1 + R_2} v_C . \] \medskip State equations. Substituting $v_L$ into the inductor and capacitor equations gives  rac{d}{dt}{i}_L &= - rac{R_1 R_2}{L(R_1 + R_2)} i_L +  rac{R_1}{L(R_1 + R_2)} v_C +  rac{R_2}{L(R_1 + R_2)} v_i, [6pt]  rac{d}{dt}{v}_C &= - rac{R_1}{C(R_1 + R_2)} i_L - rac{1}{C(R_1 + R_2)} v_C +  rac{1}{C(R_1 + R_2)} v_i. \medskip State--space representation. Defining the state vector $x = [\, i_L \;\; v_C \,]^	op$, the system can be written compactly as \[ \dot{x} = A x + B u, \] where \[ A = -\dfrac{R_1 R_2}{L(R_1 + R_2)} & \dfrac{R_1}{L(R_1 + R_2)} [8pt] -\dfrac{R_1}{C(R_1 + R_2)} & -\dfrac{1}{C(R_1 + R_2)} , \qquad B = \dfrac{R_2}{L(R_1 + R_2)} [8pt] \dfrac{1}{C(R_1 + R_2)} . \] {Mass--Spring--Damper with External Forcing (State--Space Modelling)} Question. A mass--spring--damper system shown in Figure~ is subjected to an external force input $F(t)$. The displacement of the mass from equilibrium is denoted by $\zeta(t)$ (positive to the right). The system parameters are mass $m$, damping coefficient $c$, and spring stiffness $k$. \medskip \path[draw={rgb,255:red,0;green,0;blue,0}, line width=1pt] (1, 8.5) -| (1, 6.5) -| (10, 6.75) |- (1.25, 6.75) -- (1.25, 9.5) -| (1, 8.5); \draw (1.25, 7.5) to[spring, l_={$k$}] (5, 7.5); \draw (1.25, 8.25) to[damper, l={$c$}] (5, 8.25); 
