ode[shape=rectangle, minimum width=1.215cm, minimum height=0.715cm] at (6.331, 9.753){} node[anchor=north west, align=left, text width=0.827cm, inner sep=6pt] at (5.706, 10.128){$0$}; \captionof{figure}{Mass-damper-spring system.} \medskip \item Write the equation of motion for the system in terms of $\zeta(t)$, $\dot{\zeta}(t)$, $\ddot{\zeta}(t)$, and the input force $F(t)$. \item Choose a suitable state vector and write the continuous-time state-space model \[ \dot{x}(t) = A x(t) + B u(t), \] clearly defining $x(t)$ and $u(t)$. \item If the output is the displacement, i.e.\ $y(t)=\zeta(t)$, write the output equation \[ y(t) = C x(t) + D u(t). \] \medskip \solution 1) Equation of motion: Let $\zeta(t)$ denote the displacement of the mass from equilibrium (positive to the right), and let $F(t)$ be the applied external force. By Newton’s second law, the sum of forces on the mass equals $m\ddot{\zeta}(t)$. The spring force is $-k\zeta(t)$ and the damper force is $-c\dot{\zeta}(t)$. Hence, \[ m\ddot{\zeta}(t) = F(t) - c\dot{\zeta}(t) - k\zeta(t), \] or equivalently, \[ m\ddot{\zeta}(t) + c\dot{\zeta}(t) + k\zeta(t) = F(t). \] \medskip 2) Choice of states and state equations: Choose the standard second-order state variables \[ x_1(t)=\zeta(t), \qquad x_2(t)=\dot{\zeta}(t), \qquad u(t)=F(t). \] Then \[ \dot{x}_1(t) = x_2(t), \] and, from the equation of motion, \[ \dot{x}_2(t)=\ddot{\zeta}(t) = - rac{k}{m}x_1(t) -  rac{c}{m}x_2(t) +  rac{1}{m}u(t). \] \medskip 3) State-space form: Defining $x(t)=x_1(t) x_2(t)$, the system can be written as \[ \dot{x}(t)=A x(t)+B u(t), \] with \[ A= 0 & 1 [4pt] -\dfrac{k}{m} & -\dfrac{c}{m} , \qquad B= 0 [4pt] \dfrac{1}{m} . \] \medskip 4) Output equation. If the measured output is the displacement $y(t)=\zeta(t)=x_1(t)$, then \[ y(t)=C x(t)+D u(t), \] where \[ C=1 & 0, \qquad D=0. \]

To analyse system behaviour near an equilibrium, we approximate the nonlinear dynamics using a Taylor series expansion. \subsubsection*{Scalar case} Consider a scalar nonlinear system \[ \dot{x} = f(x,u), \] and let $(x_e,u_e)$ be an equilibrium point. The first-order Taylor expansion of $f(x,u)$ about $(x_e,u_e)$ is \[ f(x,u) \approx f(x_e,u_e) +  rac{\partial f}{\partial x}\Big|_{(x_e,u_e)} (x-x_e) +  rac{\partial f}{\partial u}\Big|_{(x_e,u_e)} (u-u_e). \] Since $f(x_e,u_e)=0$ at equilibrium, this simplifies to \[ \dot{x} \approx  rac{\partial f}{\partial x}\Big|_{(x_e,u_e)} (x-x_e) +  rac{\partial f}{\partial u}\Big|_{(x_e,u_e)} (u-u_e). \] This expression describes a linear approximation of the nonlinear system near the equilibrium. \subsubsection*{Multivariable case} Now consider the nonlinear vector-valued system \[ \dot{x} = f(x,u), \qquad x \in \mathbb{R}^n, \; u \in \mathbb{R}^m. \] Expanding $f(x,u)$ about the equilibrium $(x_e,u_e)$ yields \[ f(x,u) \approx f(x_e,u_e) +  rac{\partial f}{\partial x}\Big|_{(x_e,u_e)} (x-x_e) +  rac{\partial f}{\partial u}\Big|_{(x_e,u_e)} (u-u_e). \] Again using $f(x_e,u_e)=0$, we obtain \[ \dot{x} \approx A (x-x_e) + B (u-u_e), \] where the matrix \[ A = \left. rac{\partial f}{\partial x}ight|_{(x_e,u_e)} = \left[ {cccc} \dfrac{\partial f_1}{\partial x_1} & \dfrac{\partial f_1}{\partial x_2} & \cdots & \dfrac{\partial f_1}{\partial x_n} [8pt] \dfrac{\partial f_2}{\partial x_1} & \dfrac{\partial f_2}{\partial x_2} & \cdots & \dfrac{\partial f_2}{\partial x_n} [4pt] \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots [4pt] \dfrac{\partial f_n}{\partial x_1} & \dfrac{\partial f_n}{\partial x_2} & \cdots & \dfrac{\partial f_n}{\partial x_n} ight]_{(x_e,u_e)}. \] Note that each entry $A_{ij}$ represents the sensitivity of the $i$th state equation to the $j$th state variable, evaluated at the equilibrium point. Similarly, \[ B = \left. rac{\partial f}{\partial u}ight|_{(x_e,u_e)} = \left[ {cccc} \dfrac{\partial f_1}{\partial u_1} & \dfrac{\partial f_1}{\partial u_2} & \cdots & \dfrac{\partial f_1}{\partial u_m} [8pt] \dfrac{\partial f_2}{\partial u_1} & \dfrac{\partial f_2}{\partial u_2} & \cdots & \dfrac{\partial f_2}{\partial u_m} [4pt] \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots [4pt] \dfrac{\partial f_n}{\partial u_1} & \dfrac{\partial f_n}{\partial u_2} & \cdots & \dfrac{\partial f_n}{\partial u_m} ight]_{(x_e,u_e)}. \] Each entry $B_{ij}$ quantifies how the $j$th input influences the $i$th state equation in the neighbourhood of the equilibrium. \medskip 
oindent With these matrices, the linearised dynamics in deviation variables \[ 	ilde{x} = x - x_e, \qquad 	ilde{u} = u - u_e \] are given by \[ \dot{	ilde{x}} = A 	ilde{x} + B 	ilde{u}. \] If the output equation is nonlinear, \[ y = h(x,u), \] a similar expansion gives \[ 	ilde{y} = C 	ilde{x} + D 	ilde{u}, \] with \[ C = \left. rac{\partial h}{\partial x}ight|_{(x_e,u_e)}, \qquad D = \left. rac{\partial h}{\partial u}ight|_{(x_e,u_e)}. \] \medskip {Nonlinear Planar Duorotor} Question: The nonlinear dynamics of a planar duorotor (shown in Figure~) with mass $m$, inertia $J$, and arm length $\ell$ are given by: m\ddot{p}_x &= -(u_1+u_2)\sin(	heta) m\ddot{p}_y &= (u_1+u_2)\cos(	heta) - mg J\ddot{	heta} &=  rac{\ell }{2}(u_2 - u_1) where $p_x$ is the horizontal position and $p_y$ is the vertical position. Linearise these dynamics around the hover equilibrium ($	heta=0, u_1=u_2=mg/2$) to obtain an LTI state-space model, $\dot{{x}} = A{x} + B{u}$. [scale=1.2] \def\angle{15} \def\px{2} \def\py{2} \def\arm{1.5} \draw[->, thick, gray] (0,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {$p_x$}; \draw[->, thick, gray] (0,0) -- (0,4) node[above] {$p_y$}; \draw[dashed, gray] (\px, \py) -- (\px, 0) node[below] {$p_x(t)$}; \draw[dashed, gray] (\px, \py) -- (0, \py) node[left] {$p_y(t)$}; [shift={(\px,\py)}, rotate=\angle] \draw[thick, fill=gray!30] (-\arm, -0.1) rectangle (\arm, 0.1); 
