ode [draw=gray, dashed, inner sep=10pt, fit=(kf), label=below:\smallObserver Block] (obs_box) {}; \captionof{figure}{Control architecture for the quadrotor example. The target calculator uses the filtered wind estimate \(\hat d_k\) to compute steady-state targets \((x_{ss},u_{ss})\) in the linearised model. The MPC regulator computes the virtual input \(u_{\mathrm{lin},k}\), which is then mapped to the physical commands \((\phi_k,	heta_k,T_k)\). The observer uses the measured output and the previously applied virtual input.} Substituting these virtual inputs into the linearised model decouples the motion into three double integrators, so that the discrete-time predictor used by the MPC has the form \[ x_{k+1} = A x_k + B u_{\mathrm{lin},k}. \] 3. Offset-Free Control Strategy The control loop proceeds in three stages: \item Estimation: An augmented Kalman filter estimates the state and a constant disturbance vector representing wind acceleration. The raw disturbance estimate is then low-pass filtered to reduce noise. \item Target Calculation: Given the filtered disturbance estimate \(\hat d_k\), the steady-state pair \((x_{ss},u_{ss})\) is computed from the equilibrium equations \[ I-A & -B C & 0 x_{ss} u_{ss} = B_w \hat d_k r_{\mathrm{ref}} . \] Here \(u_{ss}\) is the steady virtual acceleration required to counteract the estimated wind. \item Regulation: The MPC operates in deviation coordinates and computes the optimal corrective input sequence that steers the current state estimate towards the target. Finally, the virtual control input is mapped back to the physical commands \((\phi,	heta,T)\) using . 4. MATLAB Implementation The code below simulates this strategy. The controller uses a linear prediction model, but the plant is simulated with the full nonlinear dynamics using RK4 integration. A step wind disturbance is applied at \(t=50\) s. Figure~ shows the simulation result for tracking and disturbance observation. \centering \includegraphics[width=0.9\linewidth]{Figures/Quadrotor_MPC.pdf} \captionof{figure}{Simulation results: offset-free MPC on a nonlinear quadrotor. Top: Position tracking. The quadrotor tracks the reference setpoint \([5,5,10]\) m. At \(t=50\) s, a step wind disturbance is applied in the horizontal plane; the trajectory deviates transiently and then returns to the reference with negligible steady-state error. Middle: Disturbance estimation using Kalman Filter. The estimate converges towards the true wind disturbance. Bottom: Virtual control inputs. After the wind disturbance is applied, the controller settles to non-zero steady virtual accelerations that counteract the wind and maintain the reference position.} [language=Matlab] clear; clc; close all; g = 9.81; m = 1.0; dt = 0.1; Ac = [zeros(3,3) eye(3); zeros(3,3) zeros(3,3)]; Bc = [zeros(3,3); eye(3)]; Cc = [eye(3), zeros(3,3)]; sys_d = c2d(ss(Ac, Bc, Cc, 0), dt, 'zoh'); A = sys_d.A; B = sys_d.B; C = sys_d.C; nx = 6; nu = 3; ny = 3; Bw = B; A_aug = [A, Bw; zeros(3,nx), eye(3)]; B_aug = [B; zeros(3,nu)]; C_aug = [C, zeros(3,3)]; W = diag([1e-3*ones(1,6), 5e-3*ones(1,3)]); V = 1e-2 * eye(3); [P_obs,~,~] = dare(A_aug', C_aug', W, V); L = P_obs * C_aug' / (C_aug * P_obs * C_aug' + V); M_target = [eye(nx)-A, -B; C, zeros(ny,nu)]; P_target = pinv(M_target); N = 50; Q = diag([20 20 40, 1 1 1]); R = diag([2 2 2]); rho = 1e4; [P_term,~,~] = dare(A, B, Q, R); du = sdpvar(nu, N, 'full'); dx = sdpvar(nx, N+1, 'full'); slack = sdpvar(nu, N, 'full'); x_hat = sdpvar(nx, 1); x_ss = sdpvar(nx, 1); u_ss = sdpvar(nu, 1); obj = 0; cons = [dx(:,1) == x_hat - x_ss]; for k = 1:N cons = [cons, dx(:,k+1) == A*dx(:,k) + B*du(:,k)]; obj = obj + dx(:,k)'*Q*dx(:,k) + du(:,k)'*R*du(:,k) + rho*norm(slack(:,k),2)^2; u_abs = du(:,k) + u_ss; cons = [cons, -3 - slack(1:2,k) <= u_abs(1:2) <= 3 + slack(1:2,k)]; cons = [cons, -5 - slack(3,k) <= u_abs(3) <= 5 + slack(3,k)]; cons = [cons, slack(:,k) >= 0]; end obj = obj + dx(:,N+1)'*P_term*dx(:,N+1); ops = sdpsettings('solver','quadprog','verbose',0); controller = optimizer(cons, obj, ops, {x_hat, x_ss, u_ss}, du(:,1)); T_sim = 200; x_true = zeros(6,1); u_applied = zeros(3,1); z_est = zeros(9,1); wind_force = [0;0;0]; ref = [5; 5; 10]; log_x = zeros(3, T_sim); log_u = zeros(3, T_sim); log_d = zeros(3, T_sim); log_d_true = zeros(3, T_sim); for t = 1:T_sim if t > 50, wind_force = [1.5; -0.5; 0]; end y_meas = C*x_true + sqrt(0.01)*randn(3,1); z_pred = A_aug*z_est + B_aug*u_applied; y_pred = C_aug*z_pred; z_est = z_pred + L*(y_meas - y_pred); x_hat_val = z_est(1:6); d_hat = z_est(7:9); rhs = [Bw * d_hat; ref]; ss_sol = P_target * rhs; x_target = ss_sol(1:nx); u_target = ss_sol(nx+1:end); [du_opt, err] = controller{x_hat_val, x_target, u_target}; if err, du_opt = zeros(3,1); end u_mpc = du_opt + u_target; accel_z_total = u_mpc(3) + g; Thrust = m * accel_z_total; theta_cmd = max(-0.5, min(0.5, u_mpc(1) / g)); phi_cmd = max(-0.5, min(0.5, -u_mpc(2) / g)); Thrust = max(0, min(20, Thrust)); u_phys = [phi_cmd; theta_cmd; Thrust]; x_true = rk4_step(@quadrotor_dyn, x_true, u_phys, wind_force, dt, m, g); u_applied = u_mpc; log_x(:,t) = x_true(1:3); log_u(:,t) = u_mpc; log_d(:,t) = d_hat; log_d_true(:,t) = wind_force; end t_vec = 1:T_sim; figure('Color','w','Position',[100 100 800 800]); subplot(3,1,1); h = plot(t_vec, log_x, 'LineWidth', 2); hold on; clr = get(gca,'ColorOrder'); yline(ref(1),'--','Color',clr(1,:),'LineWidth',1.5); yline(ref(2),'--','Color',clr(2,:),'LineWidth',1.5); yline(ref(3),'--','Color',clr(3,:),'LineWidth',1.5); grid on; ylabel('Position (m)'); title('1. Position Tracking'); legend(h,{'x','y','z'},'Location','SouthEast'); subplot(3,1,2); plot(t_vec, log_d(1,:), 'k', 'LineWidth', 2); hold on; plot(t_vec, log_d_true(1,:), 'g--','LineWidth', 2); grid on; ylabel('Force (m/s^2)'); title('2. Disturbance Estimate X-Axis (KF smoothing via W)'); legend('KF Estimate','True Wind'); subplot(3,1,3); plot(t_vec, log_u, 'LineWidth', 1.5); legend('a_x','a_y','a_z'); grid on; title('3. Virtual Acceleration Commands'); ylabel('Accel (m/s^2)'); xlabel('Time Steps'); function x_next = rk4_step(fun, x, u, w, dt, m, g) k1 = fun(x, u, w, m, g); k2 = fun(x+0.5*dt*k1, u, w, m, g); k3 = fun(x+0.5*dt*k2, u, w, m, g); k4 = fun(x+dt*k3, u, w, m, g); x_next = x + (dt/6)*(k1 + 2*k2 + 2*k3 + k4); end function dxdt = quadrotor_dyn(x, u, w, m, g) phi = u(1); theta = u(2); T = u(3); Fx = T*(cos(phi)*sin(theta)); Fy = T*(-sin(phi)); Fz = T*(cos(phi)*cos(theta)); ax = (Fx + w(1))/m; ay = (Fy + w(2))/m; az = (Fz + w(3))/m - g; dxdt = [x(4:6); ax; ay; az]; end {Single-zone building heating with economic offset-free MPC} We consider a heated office room ($\sim$50~m$^2$) whose thermal dynamics are described by a three-state physically derived RC model discretised at $T_s = 1800\,	ext{s}$ (30~min) via the matrix exponential. The states are \[ x_k = T_{\mathrm{air},k} T_{w,\mathrm{in},k} T_{w,\mathrm{out},k} \!, \] representing indoor air temperature, inner wall layer temperature, and outer wall layer temperature (all in $^\circ$C). The discrete-time model is \[ x_{k+1} = A x_k + B u_k + E\,T_{\mathrm{amb},k} + B_{\mathrm{sol}}\,\varphi_{\mathrm{sol},k} + B_w\,d_k, \qquad y_k = C x_k, \] where $u_k \in [0, 2000]$~W is the heater power, $T_{\mathrm{amb},k}$ ($^\circ$C) is the measured outdoor temperature, $\varphi_{\mathrm{sol},k}$ (W/m$^2$) is the measured solar irradiance (both treated as known feedforwards), and $d_k$ ($^\circ$C/step) is an unmeasured scaled disturbance representing occupancy and internal heat gains. The output $y_k = 0.56\,T_{\mathrm{air},k} + 0.44\,T_{w,\mathrm{in},k}$ is the operative temperature (ISO~7726), measured with noise standard deviation $\sigma_v = 0.1\,^\circ$C. The pre-computed discrete model matrices are A &= 0.8753 & 0.1102 & 0.0004 0.0275 & 0.9649 & 0.0073 0.0001 & 0.0049 & 0.9851 , [6pt] B &= 7.91	imes10^{-4} 1.00	imes10^{-4} 0 \!, \quad E = 0.01404 0.00025 0.00993 \!, \quad B_{\mathrm{sol}} = 9.04	imes10^{-6} 1.43	imes10^{-6} 3.47	imes10^{-4} \!, [6pt] B_w &= 1.7647 0.0267 0 \!, \quad C = 0.56 & 0.44 & 0 . \medskip Exogenous profiles (48-hour winter scenario): \item Outdoor temperature $(T_{\mathrm{amb},k})$: \[ T_{\mathrm{amb},k} = 5 + 6\sin\!\left(	frac{2\pi(t_k-14)}{24}ight) + 0.5\,\eta_k, \] ranging nominally between $-1\,^\circ$C and $11\,^\circ$C; treated as a known feedforward. \item Solar irradiance $(\varphi_{\mathrm{sol},k})$: \[ \varphi_{\mathrm{sol},k} = \max\!\left(0,\; 600\sin\!\left(	frac{\pi(\mathrm{mod}(t_k,24)-8)}{9}ight)ight), \] treated as a known feedforward. \item Occupancy disturbance $(d_k)$: an effective scaled thermal disturbance, \[ d_k = 0.191\,^\circ	ext{C/step} & 08{:}00 \le \mathrm{time}(t_k) < 18{:}00, 0 & 	ext{otherwise,} \] corresponding to 300~W of internal gains; unknown to the controller and estimated by the Kalman filter. \item Electricity price $(p_k)$: \[ p_k = 0.28\,\pounds/	ext{kWh} & 07{:}00 \le \mathrm{time}(t_k) < 22{:}00, 0.05\,\pounds/	ext{kWh} & 	ext{otherwise.} \] Time-varying comfort bounds: \[ [y_{\min,k},\,y_{\max,k}] = [20,\,23]\,^\circ	ext{C} & 	ext{daytime }(07{:}00	ext{--}22{:}00), [15,\,26]\,^\circ	ext{C} & 	ext{night-time.} \] \medskip Control architecture (three layers): \item Augmented Kalman observer. The disturbance is appended to the state as a random walk, $z_k = [x_k^	op,\, d_k]^	op$, giving the augmented model \[ z_{k+1} = A & B_w 0 & 1 z_k + B 0 u_k + E 0 T_{\mathrm{amb},k} + B_{\mathrm{sol}} 0 \varphi_{\mathrm{sol},k}, \] \[ y_k = [C,\;0]\,z_k + v_k. \] The process noise covariance is selected as $W = \mathrm{diag}(10^{-3},10^{-3},10^{-3},\,(0.01)^2)$ is directly interpretable: $\sqrt{W_d}=0.01\,^\circ$C/step represents the expected occupancy change between sampling instants. The steady-state Kalman gain $L$ is obtained from the DARE with measurement noise variance $V=0.01$. \item Economic steady-state target calculator. At each step, the following QP selects an economically optimal steady-state pair $(x_{ss}, u_{ss})$: \min_{x_{ss},u_{ss},\epsilon_{ss}} \quad & p_k\,u_{ss} + 10^4\,\epsilon_{ss}^2 	ext{s.t.} \quad & x_{ss} = A x_{ss} + B u_{ss} + E T_{\mathrm{amb},k} + B_{\mathrm{sol}}\varphi_{\mathrm{sol},k} + B_w \hat d_k, & y_{\min,k}-\epsilon_{ss} \le C x_{ss} \le y_{\max,k}+\epsilon_{ss}, \quad 0 \le u_{ss} \le 2000,\quad \epsilon_{ss}\ge 0. \item Economic MPC regulator with price preview. Defining $	ilde x_i = x_i - x_{ss}$, $	ilde u_i = u_i - u_{ss}$, the regulator solves over a horizon $N=24$ (12~hours): \min_{	ilde u,\epsilon} \quad & \sum_{i=0}^{N-1}\!\Bigl( \|	ilde x_{i+1}\|_Q^2 + eta\,p_{k+i}\,(	ilde u_i+u_{ss})	frac{T_s}{3600} +ho\,\epsilon_i^2 \Bigr) + \|	ilde x_N\|_P^2 	ext{s.t.} \quad & 	ilde x_0 = \hat x_k - x_{ss}, & 	ilde x_{i+1} = A	ilde x_i + B	ilde u_i, & 0 \le 	ilde u_i + u_{ss} \le 2000, & y_{\min,k+i}-\epsilon_i \le C(	ilde x_{i+1}+x_{ss}) \le y_{\max,k+i}+\epsilon_i, \quad \epsilon_i\ge 0, with $Q=\mathrm{diag}(5,2,1)$, $ eta=6$, $ho=10^7$, and $P$ from the DARE. The term $ eta p_{k+i}(	ilde u_i+u_{ss})(T_s/3600)$ is the actual energy expenditure in pounds at future step $k+i$. The penalty hierarchy $ho \gg  eta\,p_{\max}\,u_{\max}\,(T_s/3600)$, i.e.\ $10^7 \gg 1680$, ensures comfort violations are never preferred over heating. MATLAB implementation: The plotting section is omitted below. [language=MATLAB] clear; clc; close all; rng(1); Ts = 1800; A = [ 0.8753, 0.1102, 0.0004; 0.0275, 0.9649, 0.0073; 0.0001, 0.0049, 0.9851]; B = [7.91e-4; 1.00e-4; 0 ]; E = [0.01404; 0.00025; 0.00993]; Bsol = [9.04e-6; 1.43e-6; 3.47e-4]; Bw = [1.7647; 0.0267; 0 ]; C = [0.56, 0.44, 0]; nx = 3; nu = 1; ny = 1; u_min = 0; u_max = 2000; A_aug = [A, Bw; zeros(1,nx), 1]; B_aug = [B; 0]; E_aug = [E; 0]; Bsol_aug = [Bsol; 0]; C_aug = [C, 0]; W_kf = diag([1e-3, 1e-3, 1e-3, (0.01)^2]); V_kf = 0.1^2; [P_kf,~,~] = dare(A_aug', C_aug', W_kf, V_kf); L_kf = P_kf*C_aug'/(C_aug*P_kf*C_aug' + V_kf); price_in = sdpvar(1); d_in = sdpvar(1); T_amb_in = sdpvar(1); phi_in = sdpvar(1); y_min_in = sdpvar(1); y_max_in = sdpvar(1); xs = sdpvar(nx,1); us = sdpvar(nu,1); ss_slack = sdpvar(1); ss_cons = [xs == A*xs + B*us + E*T_amb_in + Bsol*phi_in + Bw*d_in, ... y_min_in - ss_slack <= C*xs <= y_max_in + ss_slack, ... u_min <= us <= u_max, ss_slack >= 0]; ss_obj = price_in*us + 1e4*ss_slack^2; target_calc = optimizer(ss_cons, ss_obj, ... sdpsettings('solver','quadprog','verbose',0), ... {price_in, d_in, T_amb_in, phi_in, y_min_in, y_max_in}, [xs; us]); N = 24; Q = diag([5,2,1]); rho = 1e7; beta = 6; [P_term,~,~] = dare(A, B, Q, 1e-3); du = sdpvar(nu,N,'full'); dx = sdpvar(nx,N+1,'full'); mpc_slack = sdpvar(1,N,'full'); xhat_in = sdpvar(nx,1); xss_in = sdpvar(nx,1); uss_in = sdpvar(nu,1); Ymin_seq = sdpvar(1,N,'full'); Ymax_seq = sdpvar(1,N,'full'); Price_seq = sdpvar(1,N,'full'); mpc_obj = 0; mpc_cons = [dx(:,1) == xhat_in - xss_in]; for i = 1:N u_abs = du(:,i) + uss_in; x_pred_i = dx(:,i+1) + xss_in; mpc_cons = [mpc_cons, ... dx(:,i+1) == A*dx(:,i) + B*du(:,i), ... u_min <= u_abs <= u_max, ... Ymin_seq(i)-mpc_slack(i) <= C*x_pred_i <= Ymax_seq(i)+mpc_slack(i), ... mpc_slack(i) >= 0]; mpc_obj = mpc_obj + dx(:,i)'*Q*dx(:,i) ... + beta*Price_seq(i)*u_abs*(Ts/3600) ... + rho*mpc_slack(i)^2; end mpc_obj = mpc_obj + dx(:,N+1)'*P_term*dx(:,N+1); mpc_reg = optimizer(mpc_cons, mpc_obj, ... sdpsettings('solver','quadprog','verbose',0), ... {xhat_in,xss_in,uss_in,Ymin_seq,Ymax_seq,Price_seq}, du(:,1)); N_sim = 48*(3600/Ts); t_hours = (0:N_sim+N)*(Ts/3600); T_amb_profile = 5 + 6*sin(2*pi*(t_hours-14)/24) + 0.5*randn(size(t_hours)); Solar_profile = max(0, 600*sin(pi*(mod(t_hours,24)-8)/9)); Elec_Price = 0.05*ones(size(t_hours)); day_mask = mod(t_hours,24) >= 7 & mod(t_hours,24) < 22; Elec_Price(day_mask) = 0.28; Tmin_profile = 15*ones(size(t_hours)); Tmin_profile(day_mask) = 20; Tmax_profile = 26*ones(size(t_hours)); Tmax_profile(day_mask) = 23; d_occ_profile = 0.191*double(mod(t_hours,24) >= 8 & mod(t_hours,24) < 18); x_true = [19; 17; 10]; z_est = [19; 17; 10; 0]; u_prev = 0; log_Top = zeros(1,N_sim); log_Tmeas = zeros(1,N_sim); log_u = zeros(1,N_sim); log_d_est = zeros(1,N_sim); log_dtrue= zeros(1,N_sim); log_price = zeros(1,N_sim); log_Tmin = zeros(1,N_sim); log_Tmax = zeros(1,N_sim); log_cost = zeros(1,N_sim); for k = 1:N_sim T_amb_k = T_amb_profile(k); phi_sol_k = Solar_profile(k); y_meas = C*x_true + sqrt(V_kf)*randn; if k == 1, z_pred = z_est; else z_pred = A_aug*z_est + B_aug*u_prev ... + E_aug*T_amb_k + Bsol_aug*phi_sol_k; end z_est = z_pred + L_kf*(y_meas - C_aug*z_pred); x_hat = z_est(1:nx); d_hat = z_est(end); y_min = Tmin_profile(k); y_max = Tmax_profile(k); [ss_sol, err_ss] = target_calc{Elec_Price(k),d_hat,T_amb_k,phi_sol_k,y_min,y_max}; if err_ss ~= 0, x_ss = x_hat; u_ss = u_prev; else, ss_sol=full(ss_sol); x_ss=ss_sol(1:nx); u_ss=ss_sol(nx+1); end [du_opt, err_mpc] = mpc_reg{x_hat, x_ss, u_ss, ... Tmin_profile(k+1:k+N), Tmax_profile(k+1:k+N), Elec_Price(k+1:k+N)}; if err_mpc ~= 0, du_opt = 0; else, du_opt = full(du_opt); end u_prev = min(max(u_ss + du_opt, u_min), u_max); x_true = A*x_true + B*u_prev + E*T_amb_k ... + Bsol*phi_sol_k + Bw*d_occ_profile(k); log_Top(k) = C*x_true; log_Tmeas(k) = y_meas; log_u(k) = u_prev; log_d_est(k) = d_hat; log_dtrue(k)= d_occ_profile(k); log_Tmin(k) = y_min; log_Tmax(k) = y_max; log_price(k)= Elec_Price(k); log_cost(k) = Elec_Price(k)*u_prev*(Ts/3600)/1000; end fprintf('Total heating cost: GBP \centering \includegraphics[width=0.9\linewidth]{Figures/hvac.pdf} \captionof{figure}{Closed-loop performance of the economic offset-free MPC for the single-zone building heating example over a 48-hour simulation. Top: Operative temperature tracking the time-varying comfort region; the controller pre-heats during the cheap off-peak window before 07:00 and reduces heating during the expensive daytime tariff. Second: Heater power overlaid with the electricity price; the load-shifting behaviour is clearly visible. Third: True occupancy disturbance versus the Kalman filter estimate; convergence is fast because $CB_w = 1$. Bottom: Cumulative energy cost in GBP over the 48-hour horizon.} {Offset-free MPC of a 3-DOF Articulated Robot Manipulator} 	extsf{Problem Description} Consider a three-degree-of-freedom (3-DOF) RRR articulated robot manipulator operating in three-dimensional space. The three revolute joints are arranged as follows: joint~1 rotates about the vertical ($z$) axis (base yaw), whilst joints~2 and~3 rotate about parallel horizontal ($y$) axes (shoulder and elbow pitch, respectively). This configuration is representative of the positioning structure found in industrial serial manipulators. The control objective is to track piecewise-constant joint-angle references $r(t) \in \mathbb{R}^{3}$ in the presence of persistent disturbances (joint friction and unexpected payload changes) whilst respecting hard torque limits and soft joint-angle limits. An offset-free MPC strategy based on computed-torque feedback linearisation and an augmented Kalman filter (AKF) is employed. \vspace{0.5em} 	extsf{Kinematic Configuration} Figure~ shows the side-view projection of the arm and the definition of the joint angles $q_1$, $q_2$, and $q_3$. The base yaw axis is perpendicular to the plane of the figure. [H] \centering [ every node/.style={font=\small\sffamily}, joint/.style={circle, draw=excolor, fill=exback, thick, minimum size=7pt, inner sep=0pt}, link/.style={draw=black!70, line width=2.5pt, line cap=round}, ground/.style={pattern=north east lines, pattern color=black!40, draw=black!60} ]  ill[ground] (-0.6,-0.55) rectangle (0.6,-0.3); \draw[thick] (-0.6,-0.3) -- (0.6,-0.3); \pgfmathsetmacro{\qTwo}{55} \pgfmathsetmacro{\qThree}{-65} \coordinate (J1) at (0,0); \draw[link] (0,-0.3) -- (J1); 
