ode[font=\small\sffamily, text=purple, anchor=center] at ($(current bounding box.south) + (0, -0.65)$) {$x = [\underbrace{q_1,q_2,q_3}_{q^	op},\underbrace{\dot{q}_1,\dot{q}_2,\dot{q}_3}_{\dot q^	op}]^	op \!\in \mathbb{R}^6$ \qquad $v,\,	au,\,d_{	au} \in \mathbb{R}^3$ \qquad $y = [q_1,q_2,q_3]^	op \!\in \mathbb{R}^3$ \qquad $\hat{d} \in \mathbb{R}^3$\,(accel.\ space) }; \captionof{figure}{Block diagram of the computed-torque based feedback linearisation + MPC scheme. The disturbance $d_{	au}$~[Nm] acts on the physical plant; after computed-torque cancellation the observer estimates the acceleration-space disturbance $\hat{d} = M^{-1}\hat{d}_{	au}$~[rad/s$^{2}$].} [language=MATLAB] clear; clc; close all; rng(1); Iz1 = 1.50; m2 = 6.00; a2 = 0.45; lc2 = 0.22; I2 = 0.15; m3 = 3.50; a3 = 0.35; lc3 = 0.17; I3 = 0.08; g_acc = 9.81; Ts = 0.02; nq = 3; nx = 2*nq; nu = nq; ny = nq; nd = nu; robot_M = @(q) inertia_matrix_3dof (q, m2,m3,a2,lc2,lc3,Iz1,I2,I3); robot_C = @(q,dq) coriolis_matrix_3dof(q, dq, m2,m3,a2,lc2,lc3); robot_G = @(q) gravity_vector_3dof (q, m2,m3,lc2,a2,lc3,g_acc); Ac = [zeros(nq), eye(nq); zeros(nq), zeros(nq)]; Bc = [zeros(nq); eye(nq)]; Cc = [eye(nq), zeros(nq)]; sys_d = c2d(ss(Ac, Bc, Cc, 0), Ts, 'zoh'); A = sys_d.A; B = sys_d.B; C = sys_d.C; nz = nx + nd; A_aug = [A, B*eye(nd); zeros(nd,nx), eye(nd) ]; B_aug = [B; zeros(nd,nu)]; C_aug = [C, zeros(ny,nd)]; sigma_enc = deg2rad(0.05); R_kf = sigma_enc^2 * eye(ny); Q_state = 1e-6 * eye(nx); Q_dist = 1e-3 * eye(nd); Q_kf = blkdiag(Q_state, Q_dist); [P_ss, ~, ~] = dare(A_aug', C_aug', Q_kf, R_kf); L = P_ss * C_aug' / (C_aug * P_ss * C_aug' + R_kf); fprintf('
Observer gain L (first 3 rows shown):
'); disp(L(1:3,:)); M_target = [eye(nx)-A, -B; C, zeros(ny,nu)]; if rank(M_target) < nx+nu error('Target calculator matrix is rank-deficient.'); end N = 15; q_y = 200; R_u = 0.10; rho = 1e6; Q_mpc = C' * (q_y*eye(ny)) * C; [P_N, ~, ~] = dare(A, B, Q_mpc, R_u*eye(nu)); du = sdpvar(nu, N, 'full'); dx = sdpvar(nx, N+1, 'full'); slack = sdpvar(ny, N, 'full'); x_hat = sdpvar(nx, 1); x_ss = sdpvar(nx, 1); u_ss = sdpvar(nu, 1); v_min = -50*ones(nu,1); v_max = 50*ones(nu,1); y_min = deg2rad([-170; -90; -135]); y_max = deg2rad([ 170; 90; 135]); obj = 0; cons = [dx(:,1) == x_hat - x_ss]; for k = 1:N cons = [cons, dx(:,k+1) == A*dx(:,k) + B*du(:,k)]; dy_k = C * dx(:,k); obj = obj + dy_k'*(q_y*eye(ny))*dy_k ... + du(:,k)'*(R_u*eye(nu))*du(:,k) ... + rho * slack(:,k)' * slack(:,k); v_abs = du(:,k) + u_ss; y_abs = C * (dx(:,k) + x_ss); cons = [cons, v_min <= v_abs <= v_max]; cons = [cons, y_min - slack(:,k) <= y_abs <= y_max + slack(:,k)]; cons = [cons, slack(:,k) >= 0]; end obj = obj + dx(:,N+1)' * P_N * dx(:,N+1); ops = sdpsettings('solver','quadprog','verbose',0); mpc_ctrl = optimizer(cons, obj, ops, {x_hat, x_ss, u_ss}, {du(:,1), slack(:,1)}); fprintf('MPC compiled (N= T_sim = 600; t_vec = (0:T_sim-1) * Ts; q_true = [deg2rad(-15); deg2rad(25); deg2rad(-50)]; dq_true = zeros(nq, 1); z_hat = [q_true; dq_true; zeros(nd,1)]; v_applied = zeros(nu, 1); ref_signal = zeros(ny, T_sim); ref_signal(1,:) = [repmat(deg2rad( 0), 1, 120), ... repmat(deg2rad( 45), 1, 120), ... repmat(deg2rad(-30), 1, 120), ... repmat(deg2rad( 60), 1, 120), ... repmat(deg2rad( 0), 1, 120)]; ref_signal(2,:) = [repmat(deg2rad( 30), 1, 150), ... repmat(deg2rad( 60), 1, 150), ... repmat(deg2rad( 20), 1, 150), ... repmat(deg2rad( 50), 1, 150)]; ref_signal(3,:) = [repmat(deg2rad(-60), 1, 100), ... repmat(deg2rad(-30), 1, 150), ... repmat(deg2rad(-90), 1, 150), ... repmat(deg2rad(-45), 1, 200)]; d_true = zeros(nd, T_sim); d_true(:, 1:end) = repmat([0.50; -0.30; 0.20], 1, T_sim); d_true(:, 351:end)= d_true(:,351:end) ... + repmat([2.00; 1.50; 0.80], 1, T_sim-350); sigma_y = deg2rad(0.05) * ones(ny, 1); log_q = zeros(ny, T_sim); log_q_ref = zeros(ny, T_sim); log_tau = zeros(nu, T_sim); log_v = zeros(nu, T_sim); log_d_hat = zeros(nd, T_sim); log_d_true_acc = zeros(nd, T_sim); log_slack = zeros(ny, T_sim); fprintf('Simulation: T_sim, Ts, T_sim*Ts); tic; for t = 1:T_sim ref = ref_signal(:, t); y_true = q_true; y_meas = y_true + sigma_y .* randn(ny, 1); z_pred = A_aug * z_hat + B_aug * v_applied; z_hat = z_pred + L * (y_meas - C_aug * z_pred); x_hat_k = z_hat(1:nx); d_hat_k = z_hat(nx+1:end); rhs = [B * d_hat_k; ref]; targets = M_target \ rhs; x_ss_k = targets(1:nx); u_ss_k = targets(nx+1:end); [sol, diag_flag] = mpc_ctrl{x_hat_k, x_ss_k, u_ss_k}; if diag_flag == 0 dv_opt = full(sol{1}); slack_now = full(sol{2}); else warning('MPC infea at t= dv_opt = zeros(nu, 1); slack_now = NaN(ny, 1); end v_opt = dv_opt + u_ss_k; M_mat = robot_M(q_true); C_vec = robot_C(q_true, dq_true) * dq_true; G_vec = robot_G(q_true); tau_cmd = M_mat * v_opt + C_vec + G_vec; tau_max = [150; 120; 60]; tau_min = -tau_max; tau_cmd = min(max(tau_cmd, tau_min), tau_max); v_applied = M_mat \ (tau_cmd - C_vec - G_vec); x_rob = [q_true; dq_true]; x_next = rk4_robot(x_rob, tau_cmd, d_true(:,t), Ts, ... robot_M, robot_C, robot_G, nq); q_true = x_next(1:nq); dq_true = x_next(nq+1:end); log_q(:,t) = y_true; log_q_ref(:,t) = ref; log_tau(:,t) = tau_cmd; log_v(:,t) = v_opt; log_d_hat(:,t) = d_hat_k; log_d_true_acc(:,t) = M_mat \ d_true(:,t); log_slack(:,t) = slack_now; end elapsed = toc; fprintf('Done. Wall-clock: elapsed, elapsed/T_sim*1e3); function M = inertia_matrix_3dof(q, m2, m3, a2, lc2, lc3, Iz1, I2, I3) c2 = cos(q(2)); c3 = cos(q(3)); c23 = cos(q(2) + q(3)); h = m3 * a2 * lc3; R3 = a2*c2 + lc3*c23; M11 = Iz1 + I2 + I3 + m2*(lc2*c2)^2 + m3*R3^2; M22 = (I2 + m2*lc2^2) + (I3 + m3*lc3^2) + m3*a2^2 + 2*h*c3; M23 = (I3 + m3*lc3^2) + h*c3; M33 = I3 + m3*lc3^2; M = [M11, 0, 0 ; 0, M22, M23 ; 0, M23, M33 ]; end function C_mat = coriolis_matrix_3dof(q, dq, m2, m3, a2, lc2, lc3) s2 = sin(q(2)); c2 = cos(q(2)); s3 = sin(q(3)); s23 = sin(q(2) + q(3)); c23 = cos(q(2) + q(3)); h = m3 * a2 * lc3; R3 = a2*c2 + lc3*c23; A3 = a2*s2 + lc3*s23; dM11_dq2 = -2*m2*lc2^2*s2*c2 - 2*m3*R3*A3; dM11_dq3 = -2*m3*R3*lc3*s23; C_mat = zeros(3, 3); C_mat(1,1) = 0.5*dM11_dq2*dq(2) + 0.5*dM11_dq3*dq(3); C_mat(1,2) = 0.5*dM11_dq2*dq(1); C_mat(1,3) = 0.5*dM11_dq3*dq(1); C_mat(2,1) = -0.5*dM11_dq2*dq(1); C_mat(2,2) = -h*s3*dq(3); C_mat(2,3) = -h*s3*(dq(2) + dq(3)); C_mat(3,1) = -0.5*dM11_dq3*dq(1); C_mat(3,2) = h*s3*dq(2); C_mat(3,3) = 0; end function G = gravity_vector_3dof(q, m2, m3, lc2, a2, lc3, g) c2 = cos(q(2)); c23 = cos(q(2) + q(3)); G1 = 0; G2 = m2*g*lc2*c2 + m3*g*(a2*c2 + lc3*c23); G3 = m3*g*lc3*c23; G = [G1; G2; G3]; end function x_next = rk4_robot(x, tau, d, Ts, fM, fC, fG, nq) f = @(xx) robot_ode(xx, tau, d, fM, fC, fG, nq); k1 = f(x); k2 = f(x + Ts/2 * k1); k3 = f(x + Ts/2 * k2); k4 = f(x + Ts * k3); x_next = x + (Ts/6)*(k1 + 2*k2 + 2*k3 + k4); end function xdot = robot_ode(x, tau, d, fM, fC, fG, nq) q = x(1:nq); dq = x(nq+1:end); M = fM(q); Cdq = fC(q, dq) * dq; G = fG(q); ddq = M \ (tau + d - Cdq - G); xdot = [dq; ddq]; end \centering \includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{Figures/Robot} \captionof{figure}{Closed-loop performance of the offset-free computed-torque MPC applied to a 3-DOF spatial RRR articulated robot manipulator. The controller combines feedback linearisation (computed-torque law) with a deviation-form quadratic MPC ($N=15$, $T_s=20$\,ms) and an augmented Kalman filter for disturbance estimation. Row~1: Joint angle tracking for base yaw ($q_1$), shoulder pitch ($q_2$), and elbow pitch ($q_3$), with piecewise-constant reference trajectories (dashed) and joint limits (dotted red). Row~2: Applied actuator torques with saturation limits at $\pm150$, $\pm120$, and $\pm60$\,Nm, respectively. Row~3: Comparison of the true disturbance acceleration $M^{-1}(q)\,d$ (grey) and the Kalman filter estimate $\hat{d}$ (coloured), showing convergence after the payload step at $t=7$\,s. Row~4: Soft-constraint slack variables, which remain near zero throughout, confirming that joint limits are respected without significant violation. Constant friction biases ($0.5$, $-0.3$, $0.2$\,Nm) act on all joints from $t=0$, and an additional payload disturbance ($2.0$, $1.5$, $0.8$\,Nm) is applied at $t=7$\,s. The target calculator drives steady-state offsets to zero in all cases, demonstrating robust offset-free tracking despite unmodelled friction, sudden payload changes, and encoder noise ($\sigma=0.05^\circ$).} \section*{Chapter Summary} \item Output feedback MPC replaces full-state measurements with observer-based state estimates in the MPC optimisation loop. \item The separation principle, which guarantees independent design of estimator and controller in LQG, does not extend directly to constrained MPC and requires careful treatment. \item A disturbance model augments the plant state with an integrating disturbance, enabling the estimator to detect and compensate for persistent model--plant mismatch. \item Offset-free MPC uses the augmented observer's disturbance estimate in a steady-state target calculator to eliminate steady-state tracking errors. \item The steady-state target calculator solves a small optimisation problem at each step to find the closest feasible equilibrium consistent with the estimated disturbance. \item The observer-based MPC architecture combines an augmented Kalman filter, a steady-state target calculator, and a dynamic MPC optimiser into a modular feedback loop. \item Practical examples, including quadrotor altitude control, building HVAC regulation, and robot arm trajectory tracking, illustrate the design methodology on systems with different constraint structures. \section*{Exercises} \item Augmented State-Space Construction. Consider a scalar plant \[ x_{k+1} = 0.8\,x_k + u_k + d_k, \qquad y_k = x_k, \] where \(d_k\) is an unknown constant disturbance (\(d_{k+1}=d_k\)). \item Define the augmented state vector \(z_k = [x_k,\; d_k]^T\) and write down the augmented system matrices \(A_{\mathrm{aug}}\), \(B_{\mathrm{aug}}\), and \(C_{\mathrm{aug}}\). \item Now suppose the disturbance enters only through the output, i.e.\ \(B_w = 0\) and \(C_d = 1\). How do the augmented matrices change? \item For the two-state system \[ A = 1 & 0.1 0 & 0.95 , \quad B = 0.005 0.1 , \quad B_w = B, \quad C = 1 & 0 , \quad C_d = 0, \] write out the full augmented matrices \(A_{\mathrm{aug}} \in \mathbb{R}^{3	imes 3}\), \(B_{\mathrm{aug}} \in \mathbb{R}^{3	imes 1}\), and \(C_{\mathrm{aug}} \in \mathbb{R}^{1	imes 3}\). \item Detectability of the Augmented System. For the augmented pair \((A_{\mathrm{aug}},\, C_{\mathrm{aug}})\) constructed in Exercise~1(c): \item Form the observability matrix \[ \mathcal{O} = C_{\mathrm{aug}} C_{\mathrm{aug}} A_{\mathrm{aug}} C_{\mathrm{aug}} A_{\mathrm{aug}}^2 \] and verify that its rank equals the dimension of the augmented state. \item Now suppose the system has two outputs \(y_k = C x_k\) with \(C = I_{2	imes 2}\) and two independent disturbance states \(d_k \in \mathbb{R}^2\) with \(B_w = B\) and \(C_d = 0\). Does the augmented pair remain detectable? Justify your answer by examining the eigenvalues and the rank of the detectability test matrix \( A_{\mathrm{aug}} - \lambda I C_{\mathrm{aug}} \) at the eigenvalue \(\lambda = 1\). \item Explain the practical rule of thumb relating the number of disturbance states \(n_d\) to the number of measured outputs \(n_y\). \item Steady-State Target Calculation. Consider the system from Exercise~1(c) with the reference \(r_k = 2\) and a disturbance estimate \(\hat{d}_k = 0.5\). \item Write out the target-calculator linear system \[ I - A & -B C & 0 x_{ss} u_{ss} = B_w \hat{d}_k r_k - C_d \hat{d}_k \] with all numerical entries substituted. \item Solve for \(x_{ss}\) and \(u_{ss}\). Verify that the steady-state output satisfies \(C x_{ss} = r_k\). \item Suppose the input is constrained to \(-1 \le u \le 1\). Is the steady-state target \(u_{ss}\) feasible? If not, explain qualitatively how a constrained steady-state optimisation (as in Equation~) would handle this situation. \item Deviation-Form MPC Variables. Using the targets \((x_{ss}, u_{ss})\) computed in Exercise~3: \item Suppose the current state estimate is \(\hat{x}_k = [1.5,\; 0.3]^T\). Compute the initial deviation \(	ilde{x}_0 = \hat{x}_k - x_{ss}\). \item Write out the deviation-form prediction model \(	ilde{x}_{i+1} = A 	ilde{x}_i + B 	ilde{u}_i\) and explain why the disturbance estimate \(\hat{d}_k\) does not appear in this equation. \item If the hard input constraints are \(-1 \le u_k \le 1\), express these as constraints on the deviation input \(	ilde{u}_i\). Are the deviation-form constraints symmetric about zero? \item Explain the role of the terminal cost matrix \(P_{\mathrm{term}}\) in the MPC cost function~ and state how it is typically computed. \item Effect of Misspecified \(B_w\). Suppose the true plant has the disturbance entering through \(B_w^{\mathrm{true}} = [0;\; 1]\), but the augmented observer and target calculator are designed using the incorrect assumption \(B_w = B = [0.005;\; 0.1]\). \item Will the augmented Kalman filter still converge to a constant disturbance estimate \(\hat{d}_k\) in steady state? Explain why or why not. \item At steady state, the target calculator enforces \((I-A)x_{ss} = B u_{ss} + B_w \hat{d}_k\) and \(C x_{ss} = r_k\). Does the controller still achieve zero steady-state output offset despite the mismatch in \(B_w\)? Argue from the structure of the equilibrium equations. \item Discuss the transient consequences of the misspecified \(B_w\). In particular, how might the transient response and the value of \(\hat{d}_k\) differ from the correctly specified case? \item Comparison: MPC With and Without Disturbance Estimation. Consider a standard (non-augmented) MPC regulator that uses the nominal model \(x_{k+1} = A x_k + B u_k\) without disturbance estimation, alongside the offset-free architecture of Algorithm~. \item Suppose a constant disturbance \(d_k = d 
eq 0\) acts on the plant through \(B_w\). Explain why the standard MPC regulator generally produces a non-zero steady-state tracking error. What is the source of the persistent offset? \item In the offset-free architecture, identify which component provides integral-action-like behaviour. How does the integrating disturbance model \(d_{k+1} = d_k\) relate to classical integral action? \item Suppose instead that the disturbance is sinusoidal, \(d_k = \sin(\omega k)\). Will the offset-free MPC with a constant disturbance model (\(d_{k+1} = d_k\)) eliminate the steady-state tracking error in this case? Justify your answer in terms of the internal model principle. \item Briefly outline how the disturbance model could be modified to handle the sinusoidal case.

The architecture that best reconciles Simulink's execution model with YALMIP's requirements separates the design into two layers, as shown in Figure~. Layer 1 — the Simulink canvas contains only standard Simulink blocks and thin MATLAB Function wrapper blocks. Each wrapper declares one helper function as extrinsic, pre-allocates its outputs, and forwards its inputs. Signal routing, the feedback connection, noise injection, and input saturation are all handled by built-in Simulink blocks. Layer 2 — the helper 	exttt{.m files} contain all computation: observer updates, YALMIP calls, QP solves, and persistent state. Because they execute in the full MATLAB interpreter they impose no restrictions on the code they contain. [htbp] \centering esizebox{	extwidth}{!}{ [node distance=0.9cm and 3.2cm] 
