The methods in this chapter fall into three families, distinguished by what is learned. {Three Paradigms} \item Model Learning. Learn the unknown dynamics $f(x,u)$---or a correction to a nominal model---from data. Then use the learned model inside a standard MPC formulation. Methods: Gaussian Process MPC (Section~), Neural Network MPC (Section~). \item Data-Driven Control. Use trajectory data to construct a linear prediction model or bypass system identification entirely. Methods: Koopman/EDMD MPC (Section~), DeePC (Section~). Note: Koopman/EDMD identifies matrices $(A_K, B_K)$ from data---an indirect data-driven approach. DeePC uses data directly without ever forming an explicit model. \item Policy Learning. Use closed-loop experience from previous task executions to improve the MPC policy itself---expanding the safe region and reducing cost over repeated attempts. Methods: Learning MPC (Section~). {Connection to Earlier Chapters} Each approach builds on tools already developed in this book: \small {@{}l p{0.62\linewidth}@{}} 	oprule Approach & Prerequisites \midrule GP-MPC & Ch.\,6 (Bayesian estimation), Ch.\,7 (constrained MPC), Tube MPC Koopman MPC & Ch.\,3 (state-space), Ch.\,5 (QP/LQR), Ch.\,7 (linear MPC) DeePC & Ch.\,2 (optimisation/YALMIP), Ch.\,7 (MPC formulation) LMPC & Ch.\,7 (terminal sets, recursive feasibility)  ottomrule {When is learning necessary?} Not every MPC application needs learning. If a first-principles model is available and accurate, standard MPC (Chapter~7) or Tube MPC are preferable---they are simpler to implement and their guarantees are better understood. Learning is most valuable when: [noitemsep] \item The model is too expensive or too difficult to derive from physics. \item The system changes over time (wear, ageing, varying loads). \item The disturbance structure is unknown or state-dependent, so that fixed bounds $\mathcal{W}$ are overly conservative. Figure~ summarises the three paradigms and the methods covered in this chapter.